import { useState, useRef, useCallback, useEffect } from "react";

/* Guide data extracted from WSET L3 Study Guide document */
const GUIDE={"1": {"name": "Bordeaux", "climate": "Classification: Maritime climate, moderated by the Atlantic Ocean and the Gironde estuary. Key Influences: The Gulf Stream warms the region. The Landes forest to the west protects from Atlantic winds and moderates rainfall. The Gironde estuary and Garonne/Dordogne rivers moderate temperature extremes. Hazards: Spring frost (especially in low-lying areas), rain during harvest (dilution and rot risk), hail, and grey rot from humidity. Vintage variation is significant.", "winemaking": "Winemaking Red wines: Blending (assemblage) of grape varieties is fundamental. Extended maceration for premium wines. Ageing in French oak barriques (225L) is standard for classified growths — new oak percentage varies by estate and vintage. Malolactic fermentation is standard. Dry whites: Cool fermentation in stainless steel or barrel. Oak fermentation and lees stirring (batonnage) for premium Pessac-Leognan whites. Often a blend of Sauvignon Blanc and Semillon. Sweet whites (Sauternes/Barsac): Selective harvesting of botrytis-affected (noble rot) grapes in multiple passes (tries). High sugar concentration. Fermentation often in new oak barrels. Wines are rich, viscous, and long-lived.", "traps": ["Assuming Entre-Deux-Mers can be red. The AOC is for dry whites only. Red wines from the area are labelled Bordeaux or Bordeaux Superieur.", "Confusing the classification systems. The 1855 Classification covers the Medoc (plus Haut-Brion from Graves) and Sauternes. Graves has its own 1959 classification. Saint-Emilion has a separate, periodically revised classification. Pomerol has NO classification.", "Forgetting that Chateau Haut-Brion (Pessac-Leognan/Graves) is the only non-Medoc estate in the 1855 Classification.", "Left Bank = Cabernet Sauvignon dominant. Right Bank = Merlot dominant. Do not reverse these. *"], "takeaways": ["Left Bank = Cabernet Sauvignon on gravel; Right Bank = Merlot on clay/limestone", "Three separate classification systems: 1855 (Medoc + Sauternes), 1959 Graves, Saint-Emilion (revised)", "Pomerol has no official classification despite producing some of Bordeaux's most expensive wines", "Sauternes relies on botrytis from Ciron River mists; Semillon is the key grape", "Entre-Deux-Mers AOC = dry white only; reds from the area are labelled Bordeaux/Bordeaux Superieur"], "soil": "Left Bank (Haut-Medoc): Deep gravel beds over clay/limestone. Excellent drainage and heat retention favour Cabernet Sauvignon. The best communes (Pauillac, Saint-Julien, Margaux) sit on the deepest gravel. Right Bank (Saint-Emilion): Varied: limestone plateau, clay slopes, and some gravel. Clay retains moisture, suiting Merlot. The limestone plateau and cotes produce the finest wines. Pomerol: Clay with iron-rich subsoil (crasse de fer). Merlot-dominant; produces rich, opulent wines. Sauternes/Barsac: Varied, with clay and gravel. The key factor is proximity to the Ciron River, whose morning mists encourage noble rot (botrytis) on Sémillon grapes.", "mc": [{"q": "In the classic Bordeaux blend, Cabernet Sauvignon adds which of the following?\n1. Softness  2. Low acidity  3. Deep colour  4. High tannin  5. Blackcurrant/cassis aroma", "o": ["1, 2 and 3", "2, 3 and 4", "3, 4 and 5", "1, 3 and 5"], "a": "c", "e": "Cabernet Sauvignon is prized in Bordeaux blends for adding deep colour (3), high tannin (4), and its signature blackcurrant/cassis aroma (5). Softness and low acidity are associated with Merlot, not Cabernet Sauvignon."}, {"q": "Which of the following is NOT an effective way of combating spring\nfrost?", "o": ["Spraying with the Bordeaux mixture", "Wind machines", "Spraying with water", "Heaters"], "a": "a", "e": "Bordeaux mixture is a fungicide used to combat downy mildew, not a frost prevention method."}, {"q": "Between which two rivers does the district of Entre-deux-mers AOC\nlie?", "o": ["Dordogne and Saone", "Garonne and Marne", "Garonne and Dordogne", "Saone and Rhône"], "a": "c", "e": "Entre-deux-Mers translates to \"between two seas\" and refers to the land between the Garonne and Dordogne rivers in Bordeaux."}], "sq": [{"q": "What are the primary and secondary grapes of St-Émilion/Pomerol, and their preferred soils?", "a": "Primary: Merlot (clay and limestone). Secondary: Cabernet Franc (well-drained warm soils)."}, {"q": "Describe the St-Émilion classification system.", "a": "Integrated into appellation system, reclassified every 10 years. Within St-Émilion Grand Cru: Grand Cru Classé → Premier Grand Cru Classé B → Premier Grand Cru Classé A (highest)."}, {"q": "How is the intense, complex style of premium St-Émilion achieved?", "a": "Vineyard: Late harvest, low yields for concentrated fruit and colour. Winery: Pre-fermentation extraction, careful cap management, new oak fermentation/maturation (12-18 months)."}, {"q": "What grapes are permitted in Sauternes and what conditions does noble rot require?", "a": "Sémillon, Sauvignon Blanc, Muscadelle. Noble rot needs fully ripe grapes + humid misty mornings + sunny dry afternoons. Hand harvested in several passes."}, {"q": "Describe the climate and weather of Bordeaux.", "a": "Moderate maritime, warmed by the Gulf Stream which extends the growing season. Rain falls year-round, bringing humidity. Spring frosts are rare but harvest rains can dilute grapes."}, {"q": "What problems do grape growers face in Bordeaux?", "a": "Year-round rain disrupts flowering/fruit-set (millerandage), promotes fungal diseases (mildew, rot), and rains near harvest cause dilution."}, {"q": "What does 'Cru Classé en 1855' mean?", "a": "An 1855 classification ranking the best châteaux of the Médoc and Sauternes. Médoc estates ranked 1st to 5th growth. Indicates very high quality."}, {"q": "What vineyard conditions help Cabernet Sauvignon ripen on the Left Bank?", "a": "High stone and gravel content in the soil absorbs and radiates heat, raising vineyard temperature and allowing the late-ripening Cab Sauv to fully ripen."}, {"q": "How does a difficult vintage affect Cabernet Sauvignon style?", "a": "Incomplete ripening leads to astringent tannins, excessive herbaceous notes (green pepper, tomato leaf), less depth of fruit, and higher perceived acidity."}, {"q": "How should a mature, aged Bordeaux with heavy sediment be served?", "a": "Decanting. Remove bottle horizontally, gently extract cork, pour slowly using a light behind the neck, and stop when sediment approaches the neck."}, {"q": "What does Cabernet Franc add to a blend when unripe vs ripe?", "a": "Unripe: herbaceous or stalky notes. Ripe: vibrant fruit and floral notes."}, {"q": "What happens when Botrytis cinerea develops as grey rot instead of noble rot?", "a": "In overly damp conditions, botrytis develops rapidly as grey rot, tainting flavours, causing colour loss in black grapes, splitting berries, and causing infections. Grapes become unusable."}]}, "2": {"name": "The Dordogne & South West France", "climate": "Classification: Transitional between maritime (nearer Bordeaux) and continental (further inland). Warmer summers and colder winters than Bordeaux as you move east. Key Influences: Distance from the Atlantic means less moderating influence. Higher altitude in areas like Madiran and Jurancon. River valleys (Dordogne, Lot, Gave) provide mesoclimates. Hazards: Spring frost (especially inland), autumn rains.", "winemaking": "Winemaking Cahors: Extended maceration for colour and tannin extraction. Some producers use micro-oxygenation to soften the naturally aggressive Malbec tannins. Madiran: Tannat's extreme tannins may be managed through micro-oxygenation (pioneered here by Patrick Ducournau). Oak ageing is common. Jurancon: Sweet wines are made from grapes left on the vine to raisin (passerillage) rather than from botrytis. This is a key distinction from Sauternes/Monbazillac.", "traps": ["Confusing the sweet wine methods: Sauternes/Monbazillac = botrytis. Jurancon = passerillage (drying on the vine). They are fundamentally different processes.", "Malbec has multiple local names: Cot in the Loire, Auxerrois in Cahors. Don't confuse with Auxerrois Blanc (Alsace).", "Tannat is indigenous to Madiran, not just 'another Bordeaux variety.' It is notably tannic and full-bodied. *"], "takeaways": ["Cahors = Malbec (min 70%), known as 'Black Wine'", "Madiran = Tannat; birthplace of micro-oxygenation", "Jurancon sweet = passerillage, NOT botrytis --- key exam distinction", "Bergerac/Monbazillac use Bordeaux varieties and similar methods"], "soil": "Not a primary exam focus for this region overall. Cahors has clay-limestone soils on the causse (plateau) and alluvial soils in the valley. The best Cahors comes from the higher-altitude limestone terraces.", "sq": [{"q": "How can pruning and canopy management increase grape ripeness?", "a": "Pruning controls bud numbers, impacts yields and nutrient distribution. Open canopy maximises sunlight exposure in cool regions. In hot regions, leaf shade protects from sunburn."}, {"q": "Describe two benefits of planting vineyards on slopes in cool climates.", "a": "1) Frost mitigation: cold air sinks, so mid-slope vines avoid frost pooling in valleys. 2) Aspect: slopes receive more direct sunlight, aiding ripening."}, {"q": "What is head grafting and why is it useful?", "a": "Existing vine cut back to trunk and a new variety bud/cutting grafted on. Produces fruit by next vintage vs 3+ years for new planting. Cheaper and faster, allowing quick response to market demand."}, {"q": "Describe the effect of drought on vines and one solution.", "a": "Prolonged drought stops photosynthesis, wilts leaves, prevents ripening, and can kill vines. Solution: flood or drip irrigation from snowmelt or river water (e.g. Argentina, Chile)."}, {"q": "Name four methods to combat spring frost.", "a": "1) Heaters/smudge pots create air movement. 2) Wind machines draw warm air down. 3) Sprinklers — freezing water releases latent heat protecting buds. 4) Thoughtful vineyard design — plant on slopes, avoid frost pockets, train vines high."}, {"q": "What is powdery mildew and how is it treated?", "a": "A fungal disease thriving in warm, humid conditions. Treated with sulfur-based sprays or modern fungicides. Open canopy management promotes airflow, reducing humidity."}], "mc": [{"q": "What is the key grape variety of Cahors?", "o": ["Tannat", "Malbec", "Cabernet Franc", "Fer Servadou"], "a": "b", "e": "Cahors must contain a minimum of 70% Malbec (locally called Auxerrois or Cot). The wines are historically known as 'Black Wine' due to their intense colour."}, {"q": "How are the sweet wines of Jurançon produced?", "o": ["Botrytis (noble rot)", "Cryoextraction", "Passerillage (drying on the vine)", "Fortification"], "a": "c", "e": "Jurançon sweet wines are made from grapes dried on the vine (passerillage), not from botrytis. This is a key exam distinction from Sauternes and Monbazillac, which rely on noble rot."}, {"q": "Which technique was pioneered in Madiran to soften Tannat's tannins?", "o": ["Carbonic maceration", "Micro-oxygenation", "Cold soaking", "Saignée"], "a": "b", "e": "Micro-oxygenation was pioneered in Madiran by Patrick Ducournau specifically to manage Tannat's extreme tannins by introducing tiny amounts of oxygen during fermentation and ageing."}]}, "3": {"name": "Burgundy", "climate": "Classification: Continental climate with some maritime influence in the north (Chablis). Key Influences: East-facing slopes of the Cote d'Or catch morning sun and are sheltered from westerly rain. Altitude affects ripening: higher = cooler. Chablis is more northern and cooler. Hazards: Spring frost (a major threat, especially in Chablis), hail (devastating in some vintages), and autumn rain.", "winemaking": "Winemaking Pinot Noir: Whole-bunch or destemmed fermentation. Gentle extraction. French oak ageing (proportion of new oak varies by quality level). Malolactic fermentation standard. Rarely sees heavy extraction. Chardonnay: Barrel fermentation and batonnage (lees stirring) for premium wines (Meursault, Puligny-Montrachet). Chablis traditionally uses stainless steel to preserve purity, though some producers use oak. Malolactic fermentation is common (gives buttery character).", "traps": ["Confusing Pouilly-Fuisse (Burgundy, Maconnais, Chardonnay) with Pouilly-Fume (Loire, Central Vineyards, Sauvignon Blanc). This is one of the most common exam errors.", "Grand Cru labels may NOT show the commune name. If it just says 'Chambertin' on the label, that's a Grand Cru from Gevrey-Chambertin.", "Beaujolais is technically part of Burgundy administratively but is treated as a separate region for wine purposes. Gamay is the grape in Beaujolais, not Pinot Noir.", "Corton is the only red Grand Cru in the Cote de Beaune. Corton-Charlemagne is white (Chardonnay). *"], "takeaways": ["Burgundy = single-variety wines: Pinot Noir (red), Chardonnay (white)", "4-tier hierarchy: Regional < Village < Premier Cru < Grand Cru", "Chablis = Kimmeridgian limestone, cool climate, steely Chardonnay", "Cote de Nuits = red Grand Crus; Cote de Beaune = white Grand Crus (+ Corton red)", "Pouilly-Fuisse (Burgundy/Chardonnay) vs Pouilly-Fume (Loire/Sauvignon Blanc) --- never confuse"], "soil": "Chablis: Kimmeridgian limestone and clay — a key exam term. Contains ancient oyster shell fossils. Contributes to Chablis' mineral character. Cote d'Or: Limestone and marl (clay-limestone). The exact proportion and type vary by vineyard (climat), driving the terroir concept. East-facing mid-slope sites are prized.", "mc": [{"q": "Where would you find the term \"Grand Cru\"?", "o": ["Burgundy", "Bordeaux", "Alsace", "All of the above"], "a": "d", "e": "The term Grand Cru is used in all three regions, though it has slightly different legal definitions in each."}, {"q": "Which of the following is NOT a sub-region in Champagne?", "o": ["Côte de Sézanne", "Côte Chalonnaise", "Côte des Blancs", "Vallée de la Marne"], "a": "b", "e": "The Côte Chalonnaise is a sub-region of Burgundy, not Champagne. The Champagne sub-regions include the Montagne de Reims, Côte des Blancs, Vallée de la Marne, and Côte de Sézanne."}, {"q": "What grape variety is used to make Pouilly-Fuissé?", "o": ["Pinot Noir", "Chardonnay", "Sauvignon Blanc", "Gamay"], "a": "b", "e": "Pouilly-Fuissé is a prestigious white Burgundy appellation in the Mâconnais, made exclusively from Chardonnay."}], "sq": [{"q": "How does a cool climate influence red wine style?", "a": "Lighter body, higher acidity, lighter tannin, lower alcohol. Red fruit characters (cherry, strawberry) with possible vegetal nuances. Grape choice limited to early-ripening varieties like Pinot Noir."}, {"q": "What is chaptalisation and when is it used?", "a": "Addition of sugar (or RCGM) to must before fermentation to increase potential alcohol. Used in cool climates where grapes may not fully ripen. NOT Reverse Osmosis (that removes water, not adding to must)."}, {"q": "Name two premium Chardonnay villages in the Côte de Beaune.", "a": "Puligny-Montrachet, Chassagne-Montrachet, or Meursault (any two acceptable)."}, {"q": "What vineyard conditions produce premium Burgundy Chardonnay?", "a": "1) Well-draining limestone/chalk soils producing high-acid wines with good intensity. 2) Gentle south-east-facing slopes (côtes) providing ideal ripening. Also: low yields through green harvesting and canopy management."}, {"q": "Name three winemaking methods for complex, full-bodied Côte de Beaune Chardonnay.", "a": "1) MLF — converts malic to lactic acid, gives rounder, creamier mouthfeel, dairy flavours. 2) Yeast autolysis — extended fine lees contact with bâtonnage, adds bread/pastry/dough character. 3) Oak fermentation/maturation — French barriques contribute cedar, vanilla, and oxidative tertiary flavours."}, {"q": "Name a Burgundy Chardonnay that commonly does NOT use oak, MLF, or lees ageing.", "a": "Chablis or Mâcon Blanc."}, {"q": "How do you produce a light-bodied white wine emphasising fruit character?", "a": "Harvest early for higher acidity/lower sugar. Hand-harvest, use shallow trays. Winery: ferment in inert vessels (stainless steel), cool temperature, careful SO2 use to prevent spoilage/unwanted MLF."}, {"q": "What two processes ensure wine is clean and stable before bottling?", "a": "1) Filtration — removes micro-organisms (surface filtration expensive, can clog). 2) Addition of SO2 — prevents microbial activity and oxidation."}]}, "4": {"name": "Beaujolais", "climate": "Classification: Continental with some maritime influence from the south. Key Influences: Sheltered from the west by hills. Southern part is flatter and warmer. Northern cru villages benefit from granite hillsides. Hazards: Spring frost, hail.", "winemaking": "Winemaking Carbonic maceration: The signature Beaujolais technique. Whole, uncrushed bunches are placed in a sealed, CO2-filled tank. Intracellular fermentation occurs within each berry, producing fruity, low-tannin wines with characteristic banana/bubblegum aromas. Semi-carbonic maceration: More common in practice. The weight of grapes crushes those at the bottom; upper berries undergo carbonic maceration while lower grapes ferment conventionally. Cru Beaujolais: Top crus like Morgon and Moulin-a-Vent may use more conventional vinification and oak ageing for greater structure and ageability. Beaujolais Nouveau: Released the third Thursday of November, just weeks after harvest. Made by carbonic maceration for maximum fruit character.", "traps": ["Cru Beaujolais labels do NOT say 'Beaujolais' on the label. They only show the cru name (e.g., just 'Morgon' or 'Fleurie'). Students often fail to identify these as Beaujolais wines.", "Not all Beaujolais is simple Nouveau-style wine. Cru Beaujolais (especially Morgon, Moulin-a-Vent) can be serious, age-worthy wines.", "Carbonic maceration produces fruity, low-tannin wines — it is an intracellular fermentation, not a standard yeast fermentation. *"], "takeaways": ["Gamay is the only red grape; carbonic/semi-carbonic maceration is the key technique", "10 Cru Beaujolais --- these can be serious, age-worthy wines", "Cru labels show only the village name, NOT 'Beaujolais'", "Granite soils in the north = quality crus; clay/limestone in the south = basic Beaujolais"], "soil": "Northern crus: Granite soils, which contribute to the quality and structure of cru wines. Southern Beaujolais: Clay and limestone soils; flatter terrain.", "mc": [{"q": "Which one of the following is a Beaujolais Cru?", "o": ["Mercurey", "Montagny", "Morgon", "Margaux"], "a": "c", "e": "Mercurey and Montagny are appellations in the Côte Chalonnaise, and Margaux is a commune in Bordeaux."}, {"q": "Which of the following techniques can add flavour and texture to a white wine?\n1. Lees contact  2. Skin contact  3. Oak ageing  4. Semi-carbonic maceration", "o": ["1 and 3 only", "1 and 2 only", "1, 3 and 4 only", "1, 2 and 3 only"], "a": "d", "e": "Semi-carbonic maceration is used exclusively for red wine production, notably in Beaujolais. Lees contact, skin contact, and oak ageing can all add flavour and texture to white wines."}, {"q": "How many Crus are there in Beaujolais?", "o": ["4", "10", "21", "31"], "a": "b", "e": "The ten Beaujolais Crus are: Moulin-à-Vent, Fleurie, Morgon, Brouilly, Côte de Brouilly, Chiroubles, Juliénas, Chénas, Régnié, and Saint-Amour."}], "sq": [{"q": "What technique produces inexpensive, fruity, ready-to-drink reds?", "a": "Carbonic or semi-carbonic maceration. Results: bright colour, kirsch/bubblegum/violet aromas, sweet spices, light body, low acidity, light tannin."}, {"q": "Name two ways to add oak influence without barrels.", "a": "1) Oak chips — perforated bag inserted into vat during maturation. 2) Inner staves — oak planks inserted into stainless steel or oak vats."}, {"q": "What is de-acidification and how is it achieved?", "a": "Reducing excessive acidity in cool-climate musts by adding potassium bicarbonate or calcium carbonate to neutralise tartaric acid. A precipitate forms, removed by cold stabilisation."}]}, "5": {"name": "Alsace", "climate": "Classification: Continental with a dry, sunny mesoclimate. One of the driest regions in France. Key Influences: The Vosges Mountains to the west create a rain shadow effect, significantly reducing rainfall. East-facing slopes catch morning sun. The Rhine River moderates temperatures. Hazards: Occasional autumn rain; frost risk in spring.", "winemaking": "Winemaking Wines are typically fermented and aged in large old oak casks (foudres) or stainless steel. New oak is rarely used — the focus is on grape and terroir expression. Varietal labelling is the norm (unlike most French regions). Most wines are single-variety. Cremant d'Alsace is made by traditional method.", "traps": ["Vendange Tardive does NOT have to be sweet. VT specifies minimum sugar at harvest but doesn't dictate residual sugar in the finished wine. SGN is always sweet.", "Only the 4 noble grapes (Riesling, Gewurztraminer, Pinot Gris, Muscat) are permitted for Grand Cru, VT, and SGN. Pinot Blanc and Sylvaner are NOT (with the sole exception of Sylvaner at Zotzenberg).", "Alsace uses varietal labelling on the label, which is unusual for French AOC wines. Most French appellations label by place, not grape.", "Alsace is one of the driest wine regions in France due to the Vosges rain shadow. Students often assume it's rainy because it's northern. *"], "takeaways": ["Rain shadow from Vosges Mountains = one of driest regions in France", "4 noble grapes: Riesling, Gewurztraminer, Pinot Gris, Muscat --- only these for Grand Cru/VT/SGN", "VT = late harvest, can be dry or sweet; SGN = botrytis, always sweet", "Varietal labelling is the norm --- unusual for France", "Pinot Noir is the only red grape; Pinot Blanc is base for Cremant"], "soil": "Alsace has extremely varied geology due to the tectonic formation of the Rhine Graben. Soils include granite, limestone, clay, sandstone, and volcanic. However, specific soil-grape pairings are not a major WSET Level 3 exam focus beyond knowing that the diversity of soils contributes to the diversity of Grand Cru expression.", "sq": [{"q": "What are the benefits of hand vs machine harvesting?", "a": "Hand: grape selection in vineyard, essential for noble rot, less damage, stems retained, works on steep slopes. Machine: faster, works at night (cooler grapes), cheaper, reduces oxidation risk."}], "mc": [{"q": "Which grapes are permitted for Alsace Grand Cru wines?", "o": ["Riesling, Pinot Gris, Pinot Blanc, Muscat", "Riesling, Gewürztraminer, Pinot Gris, Muscat", "Riesling, Gewürztraminer, Pinot Noir, Muscat", "All Alsace varieties"], "a": "b", "e": "Only the four 'noble' grapes are permitted for Grand Cru, VT, and SGN: Riesling, Gewürztraminer, Pinot Gris, and Muscat. The sole exception is Sylvaner at the Zotzenberg Grand Cru."}, {"q": "What makes Alsace one of the driest wine regions in France?", "o": ["Low latitude", "The Gulf Stream", "The Vosges Mountains rain shadow", "High altitude vineyards"], "a": "c", "e": "The Vosges Mountains to the west create a rain shadow effect, blocking Atlantic moisture and making Alsace significantly drier than other northern French regions. Students often assume it is rainy because of its northerly location."}, {"q": "Which statement about Vendange Tardive (VT) is correct?", "o": ["VT wines must be sweet", "VT wines must have botrytis", "VT specifies minimum sugar at harvest but not final sweetness", "VT is the same as Sélection de Grains Nobles"], "a": "c", "e": "VT specifies minimum must weight (sugar) at harvest but does not dictate residual sugar in the finished wine. VT can therefore be dry or sweet. SGN, by contrast, is always sweet and requires botrytis-affected grapes."}]}, "6": {"name": "The Loire Valley", "climate": "Pays Nantais (west): Maritime; mild, damp, Atlantic influence. Frost risk. Anjou-Saumur: Transitional maritime/continental. Warmer inland. Layon valley provides botrytis conditions for sweet wines. Touraine: Increasingly continental. Moderated by the Loire River. Central Vineyards (east): Continental. Cold winters, warm summers. Significant diurnal temperature variation.", "winemaking": "Winemaking Muscadet sur lie: Wine is aged on its fine lees over winter until bottling in spring. Adds texture, slight spritz, and bread/yeast character. 'Sur lie' must appear on the label. Chenin Blanc sweet wines: Botrytis-affected grapes harvested in tries (selective passes) for Coteaux du Layon, Bonnezeaux, Quarts de Chaume. High acidity of Chenin balances sweetness. Vouvray: Can be still or sparkling (traditional method), dry (sec), off-dry (demi-sec), or sweet (moelleux). Style depends on vintage conditions. Sancerre/Pouilly-Fume: Stainless steel fermentation to preserve aromatics. No oak typically.", "traps": ["Pouilly-Fume (Loire, Sauvignon Blanc) vs Pouilly-Fuisse (Burgundy, Chardonnay). The #1 most commonly confused appellation pair.", "Muscadet is the appellation name, not the grape. The grape is Melon de Bourgogne.", "Sancerre makes red and rose wine from Pinot Noir as well as white Sauvignon Blanc. Pouilly-Fume is white only.", "Savennieres is a dry Chenin Blanc wine — not sweet, despite being in the same area as the sweet Coteaux du Layon. *"], "takeaways": ["4 sub-regions, west to east: Pays Nantais, Anjou-Saumur, Touraine, Central Vineyards", "Chenin Blanc = Anjou-Saumur & Touraine (dry, sweet, sparkling); Sauvignon Blanc = Central Vineyards", "Muscadet = Melon de Bourgogne, NOT the grape name. Sur lie ageing is key technique", "Pouilly-Fume (Loire/Sauvignon) vs Pouilly-Fuisse (Burgundy/Chardonnay) --- exam classic", "Savennieres = DRY Chenin Blanc; Coteaux du Layon/Bonnezeaux/Quarts de Chaume = sweet Chenin"], "soil": "Muscadet: Granite and gneiss (Sevre et Maine area). Sancerre/Pouilly-Fume: Kimmeridgian clay (same as Chablis), flint (silex), and limestone (terres blanches). Silex soils are said to give 'flinty/smoky' character to Pouilly-Fume (hence 'Fume'). Savennieres: Volcanic schist.", "mc": [{"q": "From which sub-region of the Loire does Savennières come from?", "o": ["Nantais", "Anjou-Saumur", "Touraine", "Central Vineyards"], "a": "b", "e": "Savennières is a famous appellation for high-quality, dry Chenin Blanc located in the Anjou sub-region of the Loire Valley."}, {"q": "Which one of the following is closest in style to Pouilly-Fumé?", "o": ["Anjou Blanc", "Vouvray", "Menetou-Salon", "Savennières"], "a": "c", "e": "Both Pouilly-Fumé and Menetou-Salon are dry, high-acidity Sauvignon Blancs from the Centre Loire. The other options are all Chenin Blanc-based wines from Anjou or Touraine."}, {"q": "Which of the following is incorrectly matched?", "o": ["Bourgueil and Cabernet Franc", "Menetou-Salon and Chardonnay", "Savennières and Chenin Blanc", "Touraine and Sauvignon Blanc"], "a": "b", "e": "Menetou-Salon is in the Centre Loire and specialises in Sauvignon Blanc (white) and Pinot Noir (red), not Chardonnay."}, {"q": "Which of the following sparkling wines must be made by the traditional method?\n1. Vouvray  2. Sekt  3. Cava  4. Saumur  5. Asti", "o": ["1 and 3 only", "2 and 5 only", "1, 3 and 4 only", "1, 2, 3 and 4 only"], "a": "c", "e": "Sekt is primarily made using the tank method, and Asti uses the Asti method (single fermentation stopped early). Vouvray, Cava, and Saumur are all required to use the traditional method (second fermentation in bottle)."}, {"q": "Which one of the following is a bulk-production region for\ninexpensive Sauvignon Blanc?", "o": ["Sancerre", "Mâcon", "Vin de Pays d'Oc (Pays d'Oc IGP)", "Pouilly-Fumé"], "a": "c", "e": "The Languedoc produces large quantities of inexpensive varietal Sauvignon Blanc under the Pays d'Oc IGP designation."}], "sq": [{"q": "Describe Muscadet and the sur lie process.", "a": "Melon Blanc grape. Light body, high acidity, low alcohol. Sur lie = wine rests on fine lees over winter until spring, adding body, yeast character, and slight spritz."}, {"q": "How would you describe a young Menetou-Salon?", "a": "Sauvignon Blanc. Pale lemon-green, pronounced green fruit/citrus/herbaceous/mineral aromas, dry, high acidity, light body, medium+ flavour intensity."}, {"q": "Name Loire SB appellations and describe the climate.", "a": "Pouilly-Fumé, Sancerre, Menetou-Salon. Cool Continental with low rainfall, large continentality and diurnal swings."}, {"q": "What is the dominant soil of the Loire for SB and how does it help?", "a": "Limestone (with chalk and marls). Cold soil maintains vital acidities, well-draining, allows deep root development for complexity and longevity."}, {"q": "What dessert wines come from the Loire?", "a": "Coteaux du Layon, Chaume, Bonnezeaux, Vouvray Moelleux — all Chenin Blanc. Sweet, high acidity, complex with apple, peach, honey, mineral notes."}, {"q": "Describe two methods Loire growers use to combat spring frost.", "a": "1) Chaufferettes/burners create heat preventing frost settling. 2) Sprinklers — latent heat released as water freezes maintains protective layer around buds, activated at 0 to -3C."}, {"q": "Suggest an inexpensive New World substitute for Pouilly-Fume.", "a": "NZ or Chile Sauvignon Blanc — same variety, often cheaper, similar green/citrus fruit characters."}]}, "7": {"name": "The Northern Rhone", "climate": "Classification: Continental with some Mediterranean influence from the south. Key Influences: Steep, south-facing terraced slopes maximise sun exposure. The Mistral wind (cold, dry, northerly) reduces disease pressure but can damage vines. The Rhone River moderates temperatures. Hazards: Mistral damage, drought, erosion on steep slopes.", "winemaking": "Winemaking Reds: Extended maceration, often whole-bunch fermentation (traditional). Oak ageing (various sizes). Cote-Rotie: Viognier may be co-fermented with Syrah (not blended post-fermentation). Cornas tends to be more rustic/traditional. Whites: Barrel fermented, lees contact. Marsanne-dominant whites can be full and nutty.", "traps": ["Cote-Rotie allows UP TO 20% Viognier in the blend — it is co-fermented, not blended after. Many producers use much less or none.", "Cornas is 100% Syrah and red only. No white wine is produced. No blending grapes are permitted.", "Crozes-Hermitage is NOT a sub-zone of Hermitage. It surrounds Hermitage but is a separate (larger, flatter) appellation producing more accessible wines. *"], "takeaways": ["Syrah is the only red grape. Viognier, Marsanne, Roussanne for whites", "Cote-Rotie = elegant Syrah, up to 20% Viognier co-fermented", "Hermitage = powerful, prestigious. Crozes-Hermitage = larger, more accessible (separate appellation)", "Cornas = 100% Syrah, red only, no blending permitted", "Mistral wind is a defining climatic influence --- reduces disease but can damage vines"], "soil": "Cote-Rotie: Schist and gneiss on steep terraces. Cote Blonde = lighter, more limestone. Cote Brune = darker, more iron-rich. Hermitage: Granite hillside. The famous 'hill of Hermitage' has varied granitic soils.", "mc": [{"q": "Dark, full-bodied red wines with powerful tannins produced almost\nexclusively from the Mourvèdre grape are produced wher", "o": ["Cornas", "Madiran", "Cahors", "Bandol"], "a": "d", "e": "Cornas is 100% Syrah, Madiran is predominantly Tannat, and Cahors is predominantly Malbec."}], "sq": [{"q": "Name premium Syrah appellations in the Northern Rhône.", "a": "Côte-Rôtie, Condrieu, Hermitage, Crozes-Hermitage, Cornas, St-Joseph."}, {"q": "What is the Mistral and how do growers combat it?", "a": "Cold north wind that can snap shoots and cause harvest losses. Growers support vines with stakes or tee-pee arrangements. Best sites lie in lateral valleys sheltered from the wind."}, {"q": "Why are steep south-facing slopes important in the Northern Rhône?", "a": "They lie in lateral valleys protected from the Mistral. South-facing aspect maximises sunshine and heat for ripening Syrah."}, {"q": "What is the dominant soil and how does it help Syrah?", "a": "Granite. Low fertility forces deep roots. Absorbs heat from south-facing slopes and provides good drainage, allowing concentrated flavours without excess water."}, {"q": "Describe Viognier/Condrieu.", "a": "Found in Condrieu. Low-yielding, late-ripening. Full-bodied, low acidity, medium-high alcohol. Aromas of peach, apricot, orange blossom, honeysuckle. Can be co-fermented with Syrah in Côte-Rôtie (max 20%)."}, {"q": "What white grape can be co-fermented with Syrah in Cote-Rotie and at what maximum?", "a": "Viognier, up to 20% in Cote-Rotie (co-fermented, not blended). In Crozes-Hermitage, up to 15% Marsanne and Roussanne can be added."}, {"q": "Why is Hermitage AC higher quality than Crozes-Hermitage?", "a": "Hermitage is a hill with steep slopes providing good aspect. Composed of granite — poor, well-draining soil forcing deep roots, lower yields, concentrated fruit. Crozes-Hermitage is larger and flatter."}]}, "8": {"name": "The Southern Rhone", "climate": "Classification: Mediterranean. Warm, dry summers; mild winters. Key Influences: The Mistral wind is even stronger here; stakes/bush vines (gobelet) used to protect. Very sunny. Low rainfall. Hazards: Drought, extreme heat, Mistral damage.", "winemaking": "Winemaking Blending is central — Grenache provides fruit, alcohol, and body; Syrah adds colour, structure, and peppery spice; Mourvedre contributes tannin and earthy complexity. Some Chateauneuf-du-Pape producers use large old oak foudres; others use small barriques. Carbonic maceration is used for some Cotes du Rhone for early-drinking styles.", "traps": ["Chateauneuf-du-Pape allows 13 grape varieties, but Grenache is dominant. Don't assume all 13 are used by every producer.", "Tavel is rose ONLY. It is the only French appellation exclusively for rose wine.", "Northern Rhone = Syrah only. Southern Rhone = Grenache dominant blends. Do not confuse. *"], "takeaways": ["Southern Rhone = Mediterranean, Grenache-dominant blends (GSM)", "Chateauneuf-du-Pape: 13 permitted varieties, galets roules stones, full-bodied reds", "Tavel = rose only --- only French appellation exclusively for rose", "Northern Rhone = Syrah; Southern Rhone = Grenache --- never confuse"], "soil": "Chateauneuf-du-Pape: Famous for large, rounded galets roules (pudding stones/river pebbles) which retain heat during the day and radiate it at night, aiding ripening. This is a frequently tested soil detail.", "mc": [{"q": "Where is the Tavel AOC located?", "o": ["Northern Rhône", "Southern Rhône", "Languedoc-Roussillon", "Provence"], "a": "b", "e": "Tavel is a cru in the Southern Rhône dedicated exclusively to producing rosé wines."}, {"q": "Which of the following is NOT located in Languedoc-Roussillon?", "o": ["Fitou", "Lirac", "Corbières", "Minervois"], "a": "b", "e": "Lirac is an appellation in the Southern Rhône Valley, not the Languedoc. Fitou, Corbières, and Minervois are all appellations within Languedoc-Roussillon."}], "sq": [{"q": "Describe the three main S. Rhône grapes and their characteristics.", "a": "Grenache: low tannin/colour, high alcohol, red fruit, sweet spice. Syrah: full-bodied, high colour/tannin, black fruit, pungent spice. Mourvèdre: deep colour/tannin, red fruit, develops leather/game."}, {"q": "Name affordable alternatives to Châteauneuf-du-Pape.", "a": "Gigondas, Vacqueyras, Lirac, Rasteau, Vinsobres, Beaumes-de-Venise Rouge. Same GSM grapes, similar climate, less prestige so lower price."}, {"q": "Why is Côtes du Rhône often inexpensive?", "a": "High yields permitted, lesser quality grapes (Cinsault, Carignan) used more, often carbonic maceration for simple fruity style."}, {"q": "What climatic conditions does Grenache require?", "a": "Hot Mediterranean/Continental, 2000+ sunshine hours. Hardy and drought-resistant (can survive on 250mm rain). Late-ripening so needs heat to fully ripen."}, {"q": "How do growers and winemakers produce inexpensive Cotes du Rhone?", "a": "Growers: higher yields, more buds, higher-yielding varieties (Carignan, Cinsault). Winemakers: increased proportion of simpler varieties, (semi) carbonic maceration for fruity, inexpensive styles."}, {"q": "Describe Muscat de Beaumes de Venise and how it is produced.", "a": "VDN from the Southern Rhone. Muscat grapes picked ripe, some skin contact for aromatic intensity. Cool fermentation stopped by fortification with 96% grape spirit. Stored in inert vessels. Medium gold, floral, sweet but rarely luscious."}]}, "9": {"name": "Southern France", "climate": "Classification: Mediterranean throughout. Hot, dry summers. Mild winters. Key Influences: Proximity to the sea moderates coastal areas. Higher altitude sites are cooler. Tramontane and Mistral winds reduce humidity/disease. Hazards: Drought; occasional torrential autumn rains.", "winemaking": "Winemaking Vins Doux Naturels (VDN): Fortified sweet wines. Grape spirit (mutage) is added during fermentation to stop it, preserving residual sugar. Banyuls and Maury (Grenache Noir), Muscat de Rivesaltes (Muscat). Roussillon speciality. Provence rose: Direct pressing (short skin contact) for pale, dry, fresh roses. Provencal style is very pale 'salmon pink.' Bandol: Mourvedre minimum 50%. Extended ageing required (18 months for red). Full-bodied, structured.", "traps": ["VDN (Vins Doux Naturels) are FORTIFIED, not naturally sweet. The name is misleading — 'naturel' refers to the natural grape sugar, not to the method.", "Bandol is not just a rose appellation. Its most important wines are serious, Mourvedre-dominated reds requiring 18 months ageing.", "Limoux produces sparkling wines: Blanquette de Limoux (Mauzac-based, traditional method) and Cremant de Limoux. *"], "takeaways": ["Languedoc-Roussillon = France's largest wine area; both AOC and IGP", "VDN (Banyuls, Maury, Rivesaltes) = fortified sweet wines from Roussillon", "Provence = famous for pale, dry rose; Bandol is the prestige exception (Mourvedre reds)", "IGP Pays d'Oc = major source of varietal-labelled French wine", "Bandol red requires minimum 50% Mourvedre"], "soil": "Not a primary exam focus for this region. Varied: schist in parts of Languedoc and Roussillon, limestone in Limoux, volcanic in parts of Languedoc.", "sq": [{"q": "How do you produce a still rosé wine? Describe two methods.", "a": "1) Direct pressing: black grapes pressed like whites, extracting colour but not tannin → delicate rosé. 2) Short maceration (saignée): juice left on skins 3-24 hours, then drained off and fermented as white → deeper colour and more body."}], "mc": [{"q": "What does VDN (Vin Doux Naturel) mean?", "o": ["A naturally sweet wine with no intervention", "A wine sweetened by adding sugar", "A fortified wine where spirit is added during fermentation", "A late-harvest wine"], "a": "c", "e": "Despite the misleading name ('naturel' refers to the natural grape sugar), VDNs are fortified wines. Grape spirit (mutage) is added during fermentation to stop it, preserving residual sugar. Key examples include Banyuls, Maury, and Muscat de Rivesaltes."}, {"q": "What is the minimum percentage of Mourvèdre required in Bandol red wines?", "o": ["30%", "40%", "50%", "70%"], "a": "c", "e": "Bandol red wines must contain a minimum of 50% Mourvèdre and require at least 18 months of ageing. Bandol is one of the few appellations where Mourvèdre is the dominant variety."}, {"q": "Which of the following is NOT from the Languedoc-Roussillon?", "o": ["Corbières", "Minervois", "Bandol", "Fitou"], "a": "c", "e": "Bandol is in Provence, not the Languedoc-Roussillon. Corbières, Minervois, and Fitou are all Languedoc appellations."}]}, "10": {"name": "Germany", "climate": "Classification: Cool continental. Many of the northernmost vineyards in the world. Key Influences: Rivers (Rhine, Mosel) moderate temperatures and reflect sunlight. Steep south-facing slopes maximise sun exposure. Slate soils in the Mosel retain and radiate heat. Hazards: Frost, insufficient ripening in cool vintages, grey rot.", "winemaking": "Winemaking Stainless steel fermentation is standard for preserving Riesling's purity. Some producers use traditional large oak casks (Stuck/Fuder). Dry wines (trocken) are increasingly popular. Sweet wines at BA/TBA level are made from botrytis-affected grapes. Eiswein requires natural freezing on the vine.", "traps": ["Pradikat levels indicate grape RIPENESS at harvest, NOT sweetness in the final wine. Spatlese can be dry (trocken). Only BA and TBA are always sweet.", "Chaptalization is permitted for QbA but NOT for Pradikatswein.", "Eiswein must be harvested at -7°C or below and has the same must weight requirement as BA, but is NOT botrytis-affected — it relies on freezing.", "VDP classification is voluntary and estate-driven, NOT part of German wine law. *"], "takeaways": ["Pradikat = grape ripeness at harvest, NOT guaranteed sweetness (except BA/TBA)", "No chaptalization permitted for Pradikatswein; permitted for QbA", "Mosel = steep slate, light racy Riesling; Rheingau = fuller Riesling; Pfalz = warmest", "VDP classification (Grosse Lage = Grand Cru) is voluntary, not law", "Eiswein = frozen grapes (-7C), no botrytis; same must weight as BA", "Franken: Silvaner is the signature grape; wines in distinctive Bocksbeutel bottle"], "mc": [{"q": "Which of the following wines can be produced in a dry style?\n1. Auslese  2. Kabinett  3. Spätlese  4. Trockenbeerenauslese", "o": ["1 and 2 only", "2, 3 and 4", "1, 3 and 4", "1, 2 and 3"], "a": "d", "e": "Auslese, Kabinett, and Spätlese indicate sugar ripeness levels at harvest and can be fermented fully dry (labelled as 'Trocken'). Trockenbeerenauslese (TBA) is always sweet due to the extreme concentration of botrytis-affected berries."}, {"q": "Which soil type predominates in the steeply sloping vineyard sites\nof the Mosel?", "o": ["Chalk", "Clay", "Slate", "Granite"], "a": "c", "e": "The Mosel's steep slopes are famous for their blue and red slate soils, which retain heat and reflect sunlight onto the vines, aiding ripening."}, {"q": "Which of the following is NOT found in the Mosel?", "o": ["Nierstein", "Wehlen", "Piesport", "Bernkastel"], "a": "a", "e": "Nierstein is a famous wine-growing municipality in the Rheinhessen region. Wehlen, Piesport, and Bernkastel are all famous Mosel villages."}, {"q": "The best Sekt wines are made from which grape variety?", "o": ["Müller-Thurgau", "Weissburgunder", "Grauburgunder", "Riesling"], "a": "d", "e": "While many base Sekt wines are simple blends, high-quality Winzersekt and Sekt b.A. are typically made from Riesling, which produces the finest expressions of German sparkling wine."}], "sq": [{"q": "Name two white and two red German grape varieties.", "a": "White: Riesling, Müller-Thurgau. Red: Spätburgunder (Pinot Noir), Dornfelder."}, {"q": "Why does Riesling thrive in cold climates?", "a": "Very tolerant of cold winters. Buds late, so avoids spring frosts. Accumulates sugar without losing naturally high acidity."}, {"q": "State four winery methods to protect Riesling's aromatic profile.", "a": "1) Gentle pressing with little skin contact. 2) Cold settling to clarify juice. 3) Cool fermentation in inert vessels (stainless steel). 4) Avoid MLF to preserve crisp primary aromas. Plus careful SO₂ use."}, {"q": "How is a sweet Spätlese made?", "a": "Fermentation stopped early by chilling or adding SO₂, leaving residual sugar. Must then be filtered to remove remaining yeast to prevent re-fermentation in bottle."}, {"q": "What viticultural advantages make the Rheingau excellent?", "a": "Steep slopes for aspect/drainage, south-facing for solar radiation, slate soils for drainage and heat retention, wide River Rhine reflects sunlight aiding ripeness."}, {"q": "What tertiary aromas develop in aged Riesling?", "a": "Honey, petrol, mineral, dried fruit, beeswax, pine nut, toast."}, {"q": "Why can Riesling produce balanced wines across different sweetness levels?", "a": "It accumulates sugar without losing naturally high acidity. Mid-to-late ripening allows longer growing seasons in cool climates, producing different potential alcohol/sweetness while maintaining balancing acid."}, {"q": "What storage conditions are needed for long-term wine ageing?", "a": "Avoid vibrations and strong light. Maintain cool, constant temperature (10-15C). Humid environment. Store bottles on side to keep cork moist."}, {"q": "Describe the six Pradikat levels from lightest to richest.", "a": "Kabinett: lightest, delicate, can be trocken. Spatlese: late harvest, more body/concentration. Auslese: selected overripe berries, usually sweet. Beerenauslese: noble rot berries, complex, rare. Eiswein: frozen at -8C, high sugar/acid, no botrytis. Trockenbeerenauslese: severely botrytised raisins, among finest sweet wines."}], "soil": "Mosel: Blue and grey slate on steep slopes. Retains and radiates heat, essential for ripening in this cool climate. Rheingau: Deep loess and loam over slate and quartzite. South-facing Rhine terraces. Pfalz: Varied — loess, clay, limestone, sandstone, volcanic. Germany's warmest region. Nahe: Exceptionally diverse geology — volcanic porphyry, slate, quartzite, sandstone, and clay in a small area. Rheinhessen: Loess, limestone, and clay. Mainly gentle slopes. Franken: Muschelkalk (shell limestone) — contributes to the earthy, mineral character of Silvaner."}, "11": {"name": "Austria", "climate": "Classification: Continental, with warm Pannonian influence from the east in Burgenland. Key Influences: Danube River moderates temperatures in Wachau/Kremstal/Kamptal. Lake Neusiedl in Burgenland creates humid conditions for botrytis. Hazards: Spring frost, autumn rains.", "winemaking": "Winemaking Stainless steel is standard for preserving freshness. Some premium Gruner Veltliner and Riesling see large oak. Sweet wines in Burgenland use botrytis (similar to Sauternes). Ausbruch (from Rust) is a historic sweet wine category between Beerenauslese and Trockenbeerenauslese levels.", "traps": ["Wachau has its OWN classification (Steinfeder/Federspiel/Smaragd) and is NOT part of the DAC system.", "Gruner Veltliner is NOT the same as Veltliner — there are other Veltliner varieties (e.g., Roter Veltliner, Fruhroter Veltliner). Exam answers should specify 'Gruner Veltliner.'", "Austria uses Pradikat-style categories for sweet wines (Spatlese, Auslese, BA, TBA, Eiswein) similar to Germany but with different must weight thresholds. *"], "takeaways": ["Gruner Veltliner = Austria's signature white; white pepper/lentil character", "Wachau: Steinfeder < Federspiel < Smaragd (by ABV/body). NOT part of DAC", "DAC = Austria's appellation system for regionally typical wines", "Burgenland: red wines (Zweigelt, Blaufrankisch) + sweet wines from Lake Neusiedl botrytis"], "soil": "Wachau/Kremstal/Kamptal: Primary rock (gneiss, granite) and loess terraces along the Danube. Steep terraced vineyards. Loess provides depth and water retention; primary rock gives minerality. Burgenland: Varied — sandy, clay-rich soils around Lake Neusiedl. Warmth from the lake and Pannonian influence. The flat terrain around Neusiedlersee supports both red and sweet wine production.", "mc": [{"q": "What is the correct order of Wachau classification from lightest to fullest?", "o": ["Federspiel, Steinfeder, Smaragd", "Steinfeder, Smaragd, Federspiel", "Steinfeder, Federspiel, Smaragd", "Smaragd, Federspiel, Steinfeder"], "a": "c", "e": "The Wachau classification is based on alcohol/body: Steinfeder (lightest, up to 11.5%), Federspiel (medium, 11.5-12.5%), Smaragd (fullest, 12.5%+). This is the region's own system and is NOT part of the Austrian DAC framework."}, {"q": "What is Austria's signature white grape variety?", "o": ["Riesling", "Welschriesling", "Grüner Veltliner", "Müller-Thurgau"], "a": "c", "e": "Grüner Veltliner is Austria's most widely planted and signature white grape, known for its white pepper, lentil, and citrus character. It ranges from light, crisp styles to powerful, age-worthy wines."}, {"q": "Which Austrian wine region is known for sweet wines produced using botrytis from Lake Neusiedl?", "o": ["Wachau", "Kamptal", "Burgenland", "Kremstal"], "a": "c", "e": "Burgenland's vineyards around Lake Neusiedl (Neusiedlersee) benefit from humid conditions that encourage botrytis, producing sweet wines at Spätlese, Auslese, BA, TBA, and Ausbruch levels."}], "sq": [{"q": "Describe the three categories of Wachau wine classification.", "a": "Steinfeder: lightest, up to 11.5% ABV, named after local grass. Federspiel: medium body, 11.5-12.5% ABV, named after falconry. Smaragd: fullest and most powerful, 12.5%+, named after emerald lizard. This is NOT part of the DAC system — it is Wachau's own voluntary classification."}, {"q": "What are the key characteristics of Grüner Veltliner?", "a": "White pepper, lentil, citrus, and sometimes a herbaceous note. Ranges from light/crisp to full/age-worthy. High acidity. Austria's most-planted variety. Best from Wachau, Kremstal, Kamptal."}, {"q": "How does the Austrian DAC system work?", "a": "DAC (Districtus Austriae Controllatus) designates regionally typical wines. Each DAC specifies permitted grapes and styles. For example, Kamptal DAC = Grüner Veltliner or Riesling. Wachau has opted OUT of the DAC system and uses its own classification."}, {"q": "Describe the sweet wines of Burgenland.", "a": "Produced around Lake Neusiedl where humidity promotes botrytis. Styles include Spätlese, Auslese, BA, TBA, and the unique Ausbruch from Rust (between BA and TBA in richness). Key grapes: Welschriesling, Chardonnay, Furmint."}]}, "12": {"name": "Tokaj (Hungary)", "climate": "Classification: Continental with warm autumns favouring botrytis development. Key Influences: Confluence of the Bodrog and Tisza rivers creates morning mists essential for noble rot. Warm, dry afternoons allow grapes to concentrate.", "winemaking": "Winemaking Traditional Aszu production: botrytis-affected berries are collected by hand, formed into a paste, and soaked in base wine or fermenting must. The mixture is then pressed, fermented, and aged in small oak barrels (often in volcanic cellars). Extended oxidative ageing has been traditional but some modern producers prefer fresher styles.", "traps": ["The puttonyos system has been simplified: Tokaji Aszu is now minimum 5 puttonyos (120 g/L residual sugar). The old 3--6 puttonyos scale is no longer used.", "Szamorodni can be dry (szaraz) or sweet (edes). It is NOT always sweet.", "Furmint is also made into excellent dry wines — Tokaj is not just about sweet wines. *"], "takeaways": ["Furmint = dominant grape; thin skin susceptible to botrytis, high acidity", "Tokaji Aszu: botrytis paste + base wine, min 5 puttonyos (120 g/L RS), aged 2yr oak + 1yr bottle", "Szamorodni = 'as it comes' --- can be dry or sweet", "River confluence creates essential botrytis mists; volcanic cellars for ageing"], "soil": "Volcanic: Loess and clay over volcanic bedrock. The volcanic tuff cellars maintain constant cool temperatures ideal for ageing.", "sq": [{"q": "What conditions does noble rot need and how does it affect grapes?", "a": "Fully ripe grapes + humid mornings + sunny dry afternoons. Fungus punctures skin, water evaporates in afternoon, concentrating sugar/acid/flavour. Adds honey, apricot, citrus zest aromas. Requires multiple hand-harvest passes."}, {"q": "Name three European botrytis-affected sweet wines outside Sauternes.", "a": "France: Quarts de Chaume or Bonnezeaux (Loire, Chenin Blanc). Germany: Trockenbeerenauslese (TBA). Hungary: Tokaji Aszu or Tokaji Eszencia."}], "mc": [{"q": "What is the minimum residual sugar level for Tokaji Aszú?", "o": ["60 g/L", "90 g/L", "120 g/L", "150 g/L"], "a": "c", "e": "Tokaji Aszú now requires a minimum of 120 g/L residual sugar (equivalent to the former 5 puttonyos). The old 3-6 puttonyos scale is no longer used."}, {"q": "What is the dominant grape variety in Tokaj?", "o": ["Muscat", "Hárslevelű", "Furmint", "Kékfrankos"], "a": "c", "e": "Furmint is the dominant grape in Tokaj. Its thin skin makes it susceptible to botrytis, while its naturally high acidity provides the backbone for both sweet Aszú and excellent dry wines."}, {"q": "What geographic feature creates the conditions essential for botrytis in Tokaj?", "o": ["Mountain rain shadow", "Volcanic hot springs", "River confluence creating morning mists", "Lake-effect humidity"], "a": "c", "e": "The confluence of the Bodrog and Tisza rivers creates morning mists essential for noble rot development. Warm, dry afternoons then allow the grapes to concentrate."}]}, "13": {"name": "Greece", "climate": "Classification: Mediterranean. Hot, dry summers. Some high-altitude and island locations moderate the heat. Key Influences: Sea breezes cool coastal and island vineyards. Altitude provides cooler temperatures (e.g., Naoussa at \\~350m, Nemea up to 900m). Volcanic soils on Santorini. Hazards: Drought, extreme heat, strong winds (especially Santorini).", "winemaking": "Winemaking Modern winemaking with temperature-controlled fermentation. Santorini Vinsanto: sun-dried Assyrtiko grapes, oxidative ageing. Naoussa Xinomavro: often oak-aged for structure. Retsina (flavoured with pine resin) is a traditional Greek wine but not an exam focus.", "traps": ["Naoussa is 100% Xinomavro. Nemea is 100% Agiorgitiko. Do not mix them up.", "Assyrtiko maintains high acidity despite the hot climate of Santorini. This is unusual and exam-relevant.", "Vinsanto in Santorini is from sun-dried grapes (like passito), not botrytis. *"], "takeaways": ["Santorini = Assyrtiko, volcanic soil, basket-trained vines, high acidity despite heat", "Naoussa = Xinomavro (100%), high acid/tannin, compared to Nebbiolo", "Nemea = Agiorgitiko, softer reds, altitude-influenced", "Greece's strength is indigenous varieties that maintain character in hot climates", "Santorini vines trained in basket shape (kouloura) to protect from strong winds"], "soil": "Santorini: Volcanic (pumice, ash, basalt). Very poor, low-fertility soils that stress vines, concentrating flavours. No phylloxera — vines are ungrafted and very old. Naoussa: Clay-limestone and sand at ~350m altitude in Macedonia. Nemea: Varied — clay, limestone, and sand. Altitude ranges from 250m to 900m; higher-altitude sites produce more elegant wines.", "mc": [{"q": "Which Greek grape maintains unusually high acidity despite Santorini's hot climate?", "o": ["Xinomavro", "Agiorgitiko", "Assyrtiko", "Moschofilero"], "a": "c", "e": "Assyrtiko is remarkable for maintaining very high acidity despite Santorini's extreme heat. This is unusual and frequently tested. The volcanic soil and old, ungrafted vines contribute to the wine's mineral intensity."}, {"q": "What vine training system is unique to Santorini?", "o": ["Pergola", "Gobelet (bush vine)", "Guyot", "Kouloura (basket)"], "a": "d", "e": "Santorini vines are trained in a basket shape called kouloura, where the vine is woven into a low, circular nest close to the ground. This protects the grapes from the island's fierce winds and traps morning dew for moisture."}, {"q": "Naoussa is made exclusively from which grape?", "o": ["Assyrtiko", "Agiorgitiko", "Moschofilero", "Xinomavro"], "a": "d", "e": "Naoussa is 100% Xinomavro. This grape is often compared to Nebbiolo for its high acidity, high tannin, and ability to age. Nemea, by contrast, is 100% Agiorgitiko (a softer, lower-acid red)."}], "sq": [{"q": "Why can Santorini Assyrtiko maintain high acidity in a hot climate?", "a": "The variety naturally retains acidity even when fully ripe. Volcanic soil (pumice, ash) provides mineral character. Old, ungrafted vines (no phylloxera). Extremely low yields due to harsh conditions. The kouloura training protects from wind and desiccation."}, {"q": "Compare Xinomavro (Naoussa) and Agiorgitiko (Nemea).", "a": "Xinomavro: high tannin, high acidity, comparable to Nebbiolo. Pale colour. Ages well. From northern Greece (~350m). Agiorgitiko: softer, rounder, lower tannin and acidity. Deeper colour. From Peloponnese (250-900m). Altitude affects style in both regions."}, {"q": "What is Santorini Vinsanto and how is it made?", "a": "Sweet wine from sun-dried Assyrtiko grapes (like passito/appassimento), NOT botrytis. Grapes dried in the sun to concentrate sugars, then fermented slowly. Extended oxidative ageing in barrel. Rich, amber, with dried fruit, honey, and caramel character."}]}, "14": {"name": "Northern Italy", "climate": "Classification: Continental. Fog (nebbia) common in autumn — origin of Nebbiolo's name. Hazards: Autumn rain during harvest, hail. Key Wines & Grapes — DOCG/DOC Grape Style — — — Barolo DOCG Nebbiolo (100%) Full-bodied, high tannin, high acidity, long-lived. Tar, roses, cherry. Min 38 months ageing (18 in oak). Riserva: 62 months Barbaresco DOCG Nebbiolo (100%) Similar to Barolo but slightly lighter, earlier drinking. Min 26 months ageing (9 in oak). Riserva: 50 months Barbera d'Asti DOCG Barbera High acidity, low tannin, cherry/plum. Most-planted red grape in Piedmont Gavi DOCG Cortese Dry, crisp white. Trentino-Alto Adige for cool-climate Pinot Grigio. Friuli for Italy's finest dry whites.", "winemaking": "Winemaking Nebbiolo: Traditional style = long maceration (weeks/months), large old oak botti. Modern style = shorter maceration, small French barriques, earlier accessibility. Both produce quality. Barbera: often sees oak ageing to add complexity.", "traps": ["Amarone is DRY. Recioto is SWEET. Both use appassimento (dried grapes). The difference is fermentation: Amarone ferments fully; Recioto retains sugar.", "Prosecco is made by the TANK METHOD (Charmat), not traditional method. DOCG Prosecco (Conegliano Valdobbiadene) is superior to basic DOC.", "Barolo requires longer ageing than Barbaresco. Both are 100% Nebbiolo but from different areas and with different minimum ageing.", "Barbera has HIGH acidity and LOW tannin. Nebbiolo has HIGH acidity and HIGH tannin. Don't confuse. *"], "takeaways": ["Barolo & Barbaresco: 100% Nebbiolo, high acid/tannin. Barolo = longer ageing, more structured", "Amarone = dry, appassimento, high alcohol. Recioto = sweet. Ripasso = refermented on Amarone skins", "Prosecco = Glera grape, tank/Charmat method. DOCG (Conegliano Valdobbiadene) > DOC", "Barbera = high acid, low tannin. Nebbiolo = high acid, high tannin", "Friuli = Italy's best dry whites. Trentino-Alto Adige = cool alpine, Pinot Grigio exports", "Barolo: min 38 months ageing (18 in oak); Barbaresco: min 26 months (9 in oak)"], "mc": [{"q": "Which grape variety is used to make Gavi DOCG?", "o": ["Trebbiano", "Malvasia", "Cortese", "Grechetto"], "a": "c", "e": "Gavi is a crisp, floral white wine from Piedmont made entirely from the Cortese grape."}, {"q": "What is Rufina an example of?", "o": ["Barolo", "Brunello", "Chianti", "Amarone della Valpolicella"], "a": "c", "e": "Chianti Rufina DOCG is a highly regarded sub-zone of the greater Chianti region in Tuscany, known for producing wines with excellent ageing potential."}, {"q": "What does the term 'recioto' mean on a bottle of Italian wine?", "o": ["The wine has been made from semi-dried grapes", "The wine has been fortified", "The wine has been chaptalized", "The grapes were affected by noble rot when picked"], "a": "a", "e": "The passito (drying) method is used, concentrating sugars and flavours to produce a rich, sweet wine."}, {"q": "What is the correct name for the Valpolicella made as a sweet\nwine?", "o": ["Recioto della Valpolicella", "Valpolicella Ripasso", "Amarone della Valpolicella", "Valpolicella Classico"], "a": "a", "e": "Recioto is made using the passito method (drying grapes) and the fermentation is stopped before all sugar is consumed, leaving residual sugar for a sweet, rich wine."}, {"q": "Which one of the following pairs must be made by the traditional\nmethod?", "o": ["Cava & Prosecco", "Asti & Prosecco", "Crémant & Asti", "Cava & Crémant"], "a": "d", "e": "Both Cava and Crémant are legally required to be produced by the traditional method (méthode traditionnelle). Prosecco uses the tank (Charmat) method, and Asti uses the Asti method."}], "sq": [{"q": "Describe Barolo DOCG production and style.", "a": "100% Nebbiolo, min 18 months in oak (botte or barrique), min 3 years total maturation. Style: pale garnet, very acidic, very tannic, complex — cherry, rose, tar, leather, mushroom. Great ageing potential."}, {"q": "Describe Amarone della Valpolicella production and style.", "a": "Corvina, Rondinella, Molinara grapes semi-dried in drying rooms (passito/appassimento). Min 14% alcohol. Dry, high-alcohol, full-bodied with rum & raisin, chocolate, coffee, liquorice. Classic bitter finish."}, {"q": "What does Montepulciano mean in different Italian contexts?", "a": "Abruzzo: grape variety (light, easy-drinking). Tuscany: town name (Vino Nobile uses Sangiovese). Marche: grape variety blended with Sangiovese in Rosso Piceno/Conero."}, {"q": "Describe Prosecco DOCG tank method production.", "a": "Glera grape from Veneto. 1st ferment in stainless steel (cool, no MLF/oak). Liqueur de tirage added, 2nd ferment in sealed tank. CO₂ dissolves. Filtered to remove lees. Bottled under pressure. No autolysis = fresh, fruity primary aromas preserved."}, {"q": "Describe Barbaresco DOCG and how it compares to Barolo.", "a": "100% Nebbiolo. Min 9 months in oak, 26 months total. Similar to Barolo but slightly lighter, earlier drinking. Red cherry, earth, rose, tar, mushroom, violet."}, {"q": "Describe Valpolicella DOC: grapes, style, and a regional alternative.", "a": "Grapes: Corvina, Rondinella, Molinara. Veneto. Light-medium body, red cherry, plum, herbal, spice. Alternative: Bardolino."}, {"q": "What makes Prosecco DOCG (Conegliano-Valdobbiadene) superior to DOC?", "a": "Higher quality DOCG from steep limestone hillsides in Alpine foothills near Conegliano and Valdobbiadene. More restricted area, lower yields, typically more complex aromatics."}], "soil": "Barolo/Barbaresco (Piedmont): Calcareous marl and clay. Two main soil types: Tortonian (sandy, lighter wines, Barbaresco/La Morra) and Helvetian (more calcareous, firmer wines, Serralunga/Castiglione Falletto). Valpolicella/Amarone (Veneto): Limestone and clay. Hillside Classico zone has better drainage. Friuli: Ponca (layered marl and sandstone) in Collio/Colli Orientali — gives mineral, complex whites. Soave: Volcanic soils contribute to the character of Garganega-based whites."}, "15": {"name": "Central Italy", "climate": "Classification: Mediterranean on the coast (Bolgheri); continental inland (Chianti, Montalcino). Key Influences: Altitude moderates inland areas. Sea breezes cool the Maremma/Bolgheri coast. Key Wines — DOCG/DOC Grape(s) Style / Notes — — — Chianti DOCG Sangiovese (min Medium-bodied, high acidity, 70--80%) cherry, herbal. Chianti Classico DOCG: stricter rules, min 80% Sangiovese. Gran Selezione: top tier of Classico Brunello di Montalcino Sangiovese Full-bodied, tannic, complex, DOCG (100%, locally long-lived. Min 4 years ageing called Brunello) (2 in oak). Riserva: 5 years. Released 5 years after harvest. Vino Nobile di Montepulciano DOCG uses Sangiovese (Prugnolo Gentile). Bolgheri DOC: maritime coast, Cabernet Sauvignon/Merlot blends (Super Tuscans).", "winemaking": "Winemaking Sangiovese: often blended with small amounts of other varieties (Colorino, Canaiolo, Cabernet Sauvignon). Oak ageing in various sizes: large botti (traditional) or small barriques (modern). Governo technique (refermentation with dried grapes) sometimes used in Chianti for softness.", "traps": ["Montepulciano is a GRAPE (used in Abruzzo) AND a PLACE (Vino Nobile di Montepulciano, which is made from Sangiovese, not Montepulciano). This is one of the most common Italian wine exam traps.", "Brunello = Sangiovese. It's just the local name in Montalcino. Similarly, Prugnolo Gentile = Sangiovese in Montepulciano.", "Super Tuscans are typically labelled IGT (not DOCG) because they use non-traditional grapes or methods. IGT does NOT mean lower quality.", "Chianti Classico is a separate DOCG from Chianti. Gran Selezione is the top tier within Chianti Classico. *"], "takeaways": ["Sangiovese = Brunello (Montalcino) = Prugnolo Gentile (Montepulciano). Same grape, different local names", "Montepulciano = grape in Abruzzo; Montepulciano = town in Tuscany (Sangiovese wines). NEVER confuse", "Super Tuscans = high quality, IGT label, international varieties or unconventional blends", "Chianti Classico is a separate DOCG from Chianti; Gran Selezione is top tier", "Brunello: 4yr ageing min (5yr Riserva); Barolo: 38 months (62 Riserva)"], "sq": [{"q": "How does Sangiovese contribute to Brunello di Montalcino's style?", "a": "Medium-skinned grape giving medium-deep colour, high tannin (late ripening), high acidity. Red fruit (cherry, plum), spices/herbs. Has oak affinity and excellent ageing ability."}, {"q": "Describe the climate of Montalcino and its effect on wine style.", "a": "Mediterranean with coastal breezes, low rainfall, one of the warmest parts of Tuscany. Wines achieve high alcohol (~14%), are full-bodied. Cool sea/mountain breezes and diurnal range maintain acidity. Late-ripening Sangiovese achieves high tannins."}, {"q": "What are the ageing requirements for Brunello di Montalcino DOCG?", "a": "Minimum five years total maturation: two years in barrel (botte or barrique) and three years in bottle."}, {"q": "How does extended ageing affect Brunello's flavour profile?", "a": "Oak contact (depending on age/size/origin) adds secondary flavours: cedar, smoke, vanilla, chocolate. Five years of ageing causes oxidation, developing tertiary flavours: leather, meat, wet leaves, mushroom."}, {"q": "How do Bolgheri/Maremma DOC wines differ from Brunello di Montalcino?", "a": "More maritime climate, grapes grown on plains suited to Cabernet Sauvignon/Merlot. Resulting wines are more modern, fruit-forward with more new oak influence — these are 'Super Tuscans.'"}], "soil": "Chianti/Chianti Classico: Galestro (friable maite/schist) and alberese (hard limestone). Well-drained hillside soils that stress Sangiovese for concentration. Montalcino (Brunello): Galestro, clay, limestone, and sandy soils. Southern exposure and warmer temperatures than Chianti. The varied soil types across the commune contribute to distinct sub-zone characters. Bolgheri: Sandy, clay, and alluvial soils near the Tyrrhenian coast. Maritime influence suits Cabernet Sauvignon and Merlot (Super Tuscans).", "mc": [{"q": "Brunello di Montalcino is made from which grape?", "o": ["Nebbiolo", "Montepulciano", "Sangiovese", "Aglianico"], "a": "c", "e": "Brunello is the local name for Sangiovese in Montalcino. Similarly, Prugnolo Gentile is the Sangiovese clone used in Vino Nobile di Montepulciano. This naming confusion is a classic exam trap."}, {"q": "What is the minimum ageing requirement for Brunello di Montalcino DOCG?", "o": ["3 years total (1 in oak)", "4 years total (2 in oak)", "5 years total (2 in oak)", "5 years total (3 in oak)"], "a": "c", "e": "Brunello requires a minimum of 5 years total maturation, including at least 2 years in oak (botte or barrique). Riserva requires 6 years total. The wines are released 5 years after harvest."}, {"q": "Why are Super Tuscan wines typically labelled IGT rather than DOCG?", "o": ["They are lower quality", "They use non-traditional grape varieties or methods", "They come from outside Tuscany", "IGT is a higher classification than DOCG"], "a": "b", "e": "Super Tuscans use international varieties (Cabernet Sauvignon, Merlot) or unconventional blends that fall outside DOCG regulations. IGT does NOT indicate lower quality — many Super Tuscans are among Italy's most expensive and acclaimed wines."}, {"q": "What is the key difference between Chianti and Chianti Classico?", "o": ["Chianti Classico uses different grapes", "Chianti Classico is a separate, stricter DOCG", "Chianti Classico is in a different region", "There is no significant difference"], "a": "b", "e": "Chianti Classico is a separate DOCG from Chianti with stricter rules: minimum 80% Sangiovese (vs 70% for Chianti), lower yields, and the Gran Selezione tier as its top category."}]}, "16": {"name": "Southern Italy", "climate": "Classification: Mediterranean to hot. Long, dry summers. Challenges: Drought, excessive heat. Altitude and coastal breezes moderate. Indigenous varieties adapted to these conditions.", "winemaking": "Winemaking Taurasi: Extended ageing required (min 3 years, 1 in oak). Riserva: 4 years. Often compared to Barolo for structure and longevity. Etna: Volcanic terroir at altitude (up to 1000m). Elegant, mineral, high-acidity wines — unlike typical hot-climate Southern Italian style. Marsala: Fortified wine from western Sicily. Various styles from dry (secco) to sweet (dolce), and aged classifications (Fine, Superiore, Vergine).", "traps": ["Primitivo and Zinfandel are genetically identical but produce different styles due to different climates and winemaking.", "Taurasi (Aglianico) is from Campania, NOT Puglia. It's one of Southern Italy's greatest reds.", "Etna DOC produces elegant, mineral wines unlike typical Southern Italian style — altitude and volcanic soil are key. *"], "takeaways": ["Aglianico = Taurasi (Campania), powerful/tannic, compared to Barolo", "Primitivo = Zinfandel genetically. Puglia's signature red", "Etna DOC = volcanic, high altitude, elegant --- a 'cool climate' style in hot Southern Italy", "Sicily: Nero d'Avola (warm, rich); Nerello Mascalese on Etna (elegant, mineral)"], "soil": "Taurasi (Campania): Volcanic soils from Vesuvius — tufo (volcanic rock) and clay. Well-drained, mineral-rich. Etna (Sicily): Volcanic soils at altitude (up to 1000m) — basalt, pumice, and volcanic sand. Very mineral, low-fertility. Each contrada has distinct soil and exposure, creating a terroir mosaic. Puglia: Flat, fertile plains with red earth (terra rossa) over limestone — similar to Coonawarra. Suited to high-volume production.", "mc": [{"q": "Taurasi DOCG is made from which grape?", "o": ["Primitivo", "Negroamaro", "Nerello Mascalese", "Aglianico"], "a": "d", "e": "Taurasi is made from Aglianico in Campania. It is one of Southern Italy's greatest and most age-worthy reds, often compared to Barolo for its high tannin, high acidity, and longevity."}, {"q": "What makes Etna DOC wines unusual for Southern Italy?", "o": ["They are made from international varieties", "They are fortified", "They are elegant and mineral due to altitude and volcanic soil", "They are exclusively sweet"], "a": "c", "e": "Etna wines are made at altitude (up to 1000m) on volcanic soils, producing elegant, mineral, high-acidity wines completely unlike the typical warm-climate style of Southern Italy. Nerello Mascalese is the key red grape."}, {"q": "Primitivo is genetically identical to which grape?", "o": ["Tempranillo", "Zinfandel", "Mourvèdre", "Sangiovese"], "a": "b", "e": "Primitivo and Zinfandel are genetically the same variety, but they produce different styles due to different climates and winemaking traditions. Primitivo is the signature red grape of Puglia."}], "sq": [{"q": "Compare Taurasi and Etna DOC wines.", "a": "Taurasi (Campania): Aglianico. Full-bodied, high tannin/acidity, volcanic soil. Min 3 years ageing (1 in oak). Compared to Barolo. Etna (Sicily): Nerello Mascalese. Elegant, mineral, high acidity — unusually 'cool climate' style for Southern Italy. High altitude (up to 1000m) on volcanic slopes."}, {"q": "What indigenous grape varieties define Southern Italy's wine regions?", "a": "Campania: Aglianico (red, Taurasi), Fiano and Greco (white). Puglia: Primitivo (=Zinfandel), Negroamaro. Sicily: Nero d'Avola (warm rich reds), Nerello Mascalese (elegant Etna reds), Grillo and Catarratto (whites). Basilicata: Aglianico del Vulture."}, {"q": "Describe the styles of Marsala.", "a": "Fortified wine from western Sicily. Sweetness: Secco (dry), Semisecco, Dolce (sweet). Age classifications: Fine (1 year), Superiore (2 years), Superiore Riserva (4 years), Vergine/Soleras (5+ years, dry only). Vergine uses a solera-like system."}]}, "17": {"name": "Spain", "climate": "General: Predominantly continental (central plateau/Meseta), Mediterranean on the coasts, Atlantic on the northwest (Rias Baixas). Key Influences: High altitude of central plateau (600--800m) provides continental extremes and diurnal variation. Atlantic in Galicia brings rain. Mediterranean coast is warm/dry. Hazards: Drought (central), extreme heat, spring frost.", "winemaking": "Ageing Classifications — Category Red Requirements White Requirements — — — Joven Little or no oak ageing Little or no oak ageing Crianza Min 2 years ageing, 6--12 Min 18 months, 6 months in months in oak (varies by oak region) Reserva Min 3 years total, 12 Min 2 years, 6 months in months in oak oak Gran Reserva Min 5 years total, 18 Min 4 years, 6 months in months in oak oak.", "traps": ["Oloroso Sherry is naturally DRY. Cream Sherry is sweet (Oloroso + sweetening). Do not assume all dark Sherries are sweet.", "Manzanilla is only from Sanlucar de Barrameda. It is otherwise the same biological ageing process as Fino.", "Spain has only TWO DOCa regions: Rioja and Priorat. All others are DO.", "Tempranillo has many names: Tinto Fino/Tinta del Pais (Ribera del Duero), Cencibel (La Mancha), Tinta Roriz/Aragonez (Portugal). *"], "takeaways": ["Rioja: Tempranillo, American/French oak, Crianza/Reserva/Gran Reserva ageing system", "Sherry: Fino/Manzanilla = biological (flor); Oloroso = oxidative (no flor, DRY); solera blending", "Priorat = DOCa status, llicorella slate soils, Garnacha/Carinena, powerful reds", "Cava = traditional method sparkling, Macabeo/Xarel-lo/Parellada, mostly from Penedes", "Tempranillo = Tinto Fino (Ribera), Cencibel (La Mancha), Tinta Roriz (Portugal)"], "mc": [{"q": "What are Vinos de Pagos?", "o": ["Red wines from Chile", "Fortified wines from Spain", "Wines from a single estate with a high reputation", "Simple, inexpensive wines"], "a": "c", "e": "This is a Spanish classification for exceptional single estates that exist outside the standard DO/DOCa framework."}, {"q": "The grapes used to make Cava can come from:", "o": ["Anywhere in Spain", "Penedès only", "From a number of delimited regions throughout Spain", "Catalunya only"], "a": "c", "e": "While the vast majority of Cava is produced in Catalunya/Penedès, the DO legally encompasses several distinct non-contiguous production zones."}, {"q": "Which of the following does not lie along the Duero River?", "o": ["Douro Valley", "Toro", "Rueda", "Rioja"], "a": "d", "e": "Rioja is situated along the Ebro River, not the Duero. The Douro/Duero runs through Portugal (Douro Valley) and Spain (Toro, Rueda, Ribera del Duero)."}, {"q": "What is the principal black grape variety of DO Bierzo?", "o": ["Tempranillo", "Mazuelo", "Monastrell", "Mencía"], "a": "d", "e": "Bierzo, located in north-west Spain, is highly regarded for its elegant red wines made predominantly from the Mencía grape variety."}, {"q": "What is the Spanish equivalent of the French AC (AOC)?", "o": ["Vino de Mesa", "D.O.C.G.", "Qualitätswein", "D.O. (Denominación de Origen)"], "a": "d", "e": "The DO is Spain's principal wine quality classification, broadly equivalent to France's AOC/AC system."}], "sq": [{"q": "Describe Rioja Reserva vs Joven ageing and style impact.", "a": "Reserva: min 12 months barrel + 24 months bottle (36 total). Promotes tertiary characters (leather, earth) and secondary (oak, vanilla). Joven: released spring after harvest, no oak. Vibrant primary flavours only."}, {"q": "Describe Ribera del Duero climate and wine style.", "a": "Warm continental, short hot dry summers, very cold winters. Grapes ripen well (high alcohol) but high altitude (850m+) and large diurnal range ensure high acidity and tannin. Dark, concentrated, high-acid wines with clear oak influence."}, {"q": "Where is Garnacha used for powerful, deep wines with oak? Describe natural and human factors.", "a": "Priorat DOCa. Natural: Llicorella (decomposed slate) drains well, absorbs heat. Mediterranean climate, winter rainfall. Human: Terraced vineyards, very low yields through green harvesting and pruning."}, {"q": "Describe the style of Gran Reserva White Rioja.", "a": "Made from Viura. Extended ageing in American (or French) oak and bottle with controlled oxidation. Deep golden colour, tertiary characters, nutty aromas/flavours."}, {"q": "How does the Solera system work?", "a": "Maturation system of butt groups with different average ages. Wine drawn from solera (oldest). Replenished from first criadera (next youngest), which is replenished from subsequent criaderas. Each level partially emptied, blended, used to top up level below. Youngest receives sobretabla (new wine). Ensures consistency."}, {"q": "Name two oxidatively-aged Sherry styles and two qualifying for age-indicated status.", "a": "Oxidative (no flor): Oloroso, Pedro Ximenez. Age-indicated: Amontillado, Palo Cortado, Oloroso, Pedro Ximenez (any two)."}], "soil": "Rioja: Clay-limestone (Rioja Alta/Alavesa — finer, more acidic wines), alluvial clay-iron (Rioja Oriental — fuller, less refined). Priorat: Llicorella — decomposed slate/schist. Very poor soil, excellent drainage, forces deep roots. Retains heat. Key exam term. Ribera del Duero: Limestone and chalk at high altitude (850m+). Rueda: Stony, sandy soils suited to Verdejo. Rias Baixas: Granite and sandy soils. Sherry (Jerez): Albariza — white chalk/limestone. Reflects sunlight, retains moisture. The best Sherry vineyards are on albariza."}, "18": {"name": "Portugal", "climate": "Overview: Ranges from cool, wet Atlantic in the northwest (Vinho Verde) to hot, dry continental in the interior (Douro, Alentejo). Key Influences: Atlantic influence strongest in Vinho Verde and Bairrada. Continental extremes in the Douro Valley. Altitude moderates heat in Dao.", "winemaking": "Port Wine — Style Ageing Character — — — Ruby Port Short ageing in large Young, fruity, simple. Deep vessels/tank red colour Reserve Ruby Longer ageing in More concentrated, higher large vessels quality than basic Ruby Late Bottled 4--6 years in large Single vintage. Ready to Vintage (LBV) vessels drink. Rich but not as complex as Vintage Vintage Port Min 2 years in bottle Finest single-vintage Port. (Vintage) after large vessel Declared in great years ageing only. Needs extended bottle ageing (decades) Tawny Port Extended oxidative Amber/tawny colour. Nutty, ageing in small caramel, dried fruit. Aged barrels (pipes) Tawny: 10, 20, 30, 40+ years indicated Colheita Single vintage tawny, Shows vintage character with oxidative complexity.", "traps": ["Vintage Port (declared Vintage) needs DECADES of bottle ageing. LBV is ready to drink on release. Don't confuse.", "Tawny Port gets its colour from OXIDATION in small barrels, not from blending red and white. The long ageing turns it amber.", "Madeira grape names indicate sweetness level: Sercial (driest) to Malmsey (sweetest). Remember the order.", "Tinta Roriz (Portugal) = Tempranillo (Spain) = Aragonez (Alentejo). Same grape, different names. *"], "takeaways": ["Port: fortified during fermentation. Ruby = reductive ageing. Tawny = oxidative in small barrels", "Vintage Port: declared single vintage, needs decades of ageing. LBV: ready to drink", "Madeira: Sercial (dry) > Verdelho > Bual > Malmsey (sweet). Estufagem = heating process", "Touriga Nacional = Portugal's finest red grape; Tinta Roriz = Tempranillo", "Vinho Verde = light, crisp, Atlantic; Alentejo = hot, full-bodied reds"], "sq": [{"q": "Describe the Douro Valley climate.", "a": "Broadly warm continental with large diurnal swings. Shielded from Atlantic by Serra do Marão. Varies from Baixo Corgo (cooler/wetter) to Douro Superior (warmer/drier)."}, {"q": "What are Socalcos and Patamares?", "a": "Socalcos: traditional narrow terraces with stone walls, expensive, no mechanisation. Patamares: modern terraces without stone walls, allow some mechanisation, follow land contours."}, {"q": "Explain how Port is made sweet.", "a": "Grapes fermented in lagares for 24-36 hours to reach 5-9% ABV. Aguardente (grape spirit at ~77%) added, killing yeast, stopping fermentation early, leaving residual sugar."}, {"q": "How does Vintage Port mature and why must it be decanted?", "a": "Initial barrel/vat maturation for 2 years then extensive bottle ageing. Develops from primary black fruit to tertiary dried fruit, leather, tobacco. Bottled unfiltered so heavy sediment forms as tannins break down — must decant."}, {"q": "Name four extraction techniques used in Port production.", "a": "1) Foot treading in lagares. 2) Autovinifiers (automated pumping). 3) Robotic lagares (mechanised treading). 4) Piston plungers (mechanical punch-down)."}], "soil": "Douro Valley: Schist (xisto) — hard metamorphic rock that vines must crack through. Retains heat, poor fertility, excellent drainage. Terraced vineyards (socalcos/patamares). Vinho Verde: Granite and sandy soils in the northwest. Dao: Granite, producing structured, mineral reds. Alentejo: Varied — granite, schist, clay, limestone. Flat, warm plains suited to full-bodied reds.", "mc": [{"q": "What distinguishes LBV Port from Vintage Port?", "o": ["LBV is older", "LBV is ready to drink on release; Vintage Port needs decades of bottle ageing", "LBV is sweeter", "LBV uses better grape varieties"], "a": "b", "e": "LBV (Late Bottled Vintage) spends 4-6 years in large vessels and is usually filtered, making it ready to drink on release. Vintage Port (declared Vintage) needs decades of bottle ageing and must be decanted due to heavy sediment."}, {"q": "What is the correct order of Madeira grape varieties from driest to sweetest?", "o": ["Malmsey, Bual, Verdelho, Sercial", "Sercial, Verdelho, Bual, Malmsey", "Verdelho, Sercial, Malmsey, Bual", "Bual, Malmsey, Sercial, Verdelho"], "a": "b", "e": "The order from driest to sweetest is: Sercial (driest), Verdelho (off-dry), Bual (medium-sweet), Malmsey (sweetest). Remember: the grape name indicates the sweetness level."}, {"q": "How does Tawny Port get its amber colour?", "o": ["Blending red and white Port", "Extended oxidative ageing in small barrels", "Adding caramel colouring", "Using Tinta Amarela grapes"], "a": "b", "e": "Tawny Port develops its amber/tawny colour through extended oxidative ageing in small barrels (pipes of ~550L). The oxygen exposure gradually changes the colour from deep red to amber and develops nutty, caramel, dried fruit flavours."}]}, "19": {"name": "California", "climate": "Classification: Mediterranean (warm, dry summers; mild, wet winters). Huge variation across the state. Key Influences: Pacific Ocean and San Francisco Bay create fog and cool breezes that moderate coastal valleys (Carneros, Sonoma Coast, Santa Barbara). Inland areas are much warmer (Central Valley). The Transverse Ranges of Santa Barbara County run east-west, funnelling cool Pacific air inland. Hazards: Drought, wildfire, excessive heat inland.", "winemaking": "Winemaking Oak ageing (French and American) is common for premium Cabernet Sauvignon and Chardonnay. Ripe, fruit-forward styles are typical. Many Chardonnays see malolactic fermentation and oak. Some producers pursue more restrained, European-influenced styles.", "traps": ["AVAs regulate GEOGRAPHY only, not grapes or winemaking. This is fundamentally different from European AOC/DOC systems.", "Central Valley produces most of California's wine volume, not Napa. Napa is prestigious but small.", "Fog from the Pacific is what allows cool-climate viticulture in otherwise warm California. Without fog, regions like Carneros and Russian River would be too warm. *"], "takeaways": ["AVA = geography only; no grape/yield/winemaking rules (unlike EU appellations)", "Napa = Cabernet Sauvignon; Sonoma = more diverse (Pinot Noir, Chardonnay, Zinfandel)", "Pacific fog is the key moderating influence for coastal California viticulture", "Central Valley = bulk production (most volume); Napa = prestige (small % of total)", "85% of grapes must come from a named AVA to use that AVA on the label"], "mc": [{"q": "Which AVA in California is well-known for having some of the\noldest Zinfandel vineyards in the state?", "o": ["Santa Barbara", "Los Carneros", "Anderson Valley", "Lodi"], "a": "d", "e": "Lodi in California's Central Valley is famous for its ancient, head-trained Zinfandel vines, many over 100 years old."}], "sq": [{"q": "What Italian grape is Zinfandel related to?", "a": "Primitivo."}, {"q": "What is White Zinfandel and how is it made?", "a": "A pale pink/salmon rosé from black Zinfandel grapes. Short maceration extracts light colour. Fermentation arrested by chilling and filtering out yeast, leaving residual sugar and low alcohol."}, {"q": "How does Zinfandel's uneven ripening affect red wine style?", "a": "Produces both under-ripe and raisined fruit. Raisining yields concentrated, full-bodied, high-alcohol wines with possible residual sugar and flavours of cooked/dried berries, liquorice. Under-ripe fruit adds herbal/herbaceous notes."}, {"q": "Name two premium AVAs within Napa Valley.", "a": "Any of: Howell Mountain, Calistoga, St Helena, Rutherford, Oakville, Stag's Leap, Mount Veeder, Los Carneros."}, {"q": "Name three climatic/geographical factors that make Napa Valley premium.", "a": "1) San Pablo Bay cool afternoon breezes reduce temperatures (Carneros ~10°C cooler than central Napa). 2) Morning fogs (6-9am) moderate temperature up to 1400ft, maintaining acidity. 3) Mayacamas (west) and Vaca (east) mountains create heat trap in central Napa (Rutherford, Oakville) for greater ripeness."}, {"q": "How do mountain AVA wines (Howell Mountain, Atlas Peak) differ from valley floor Napa?", "a": "Higher altitude = cooler, longer growing season → higher acidity and greater tannin. Steep slopes provide better aspect/ripeness. Valley floor wines are riper, softer, rounder with gentler tannins."}, {"q": "Why does Napa's proximity to San Pablo Bay create premium Cabernet Sauvignon?", "a": "Cool Pacific air meets warm continental air, producing fogs that refresh vineyards and maintain high acidity for balanced wines. The cold Pacific also tempers Napa's hot Mediterranean climate."}, {"q": "Name bulk-volume and premium Chardonnay areas in California.", "a": "Bulk: Central Valley. Premium: Sonoma Coast AVA, Russian River AVA, Napa Valley AVA, Carneros AVA."}, {"q": "What vineyard conditions produce premium California Chardonnay?", "a": "Coastal ranges/hillsides offer cooling from altitude and sea proximity. Fogs form where Pacific and continental air meet, creating balance and marked acidity. Also: low yields, green harvesting, canopy management."}, {"q": "How do producers achieve a toasted oak style in inexpensive Chardonnay?", "a": "Using charred/toasted oak staves or chips immersed directly in the wine, rather than expensive barrels — an effective, inexpensive shortcut."}], "soil": "Napa Valley: Extremely varied — over 30 soil types. Alluvial gravels on the valley floor (Rutherford, Oakville) provide excellent drainage for Cabernet Sauvignon. Mountain sites (Howell Mountain, Mount Veeder) have volcanic and rocky soils. Carneros has shallow clay over bedrock. Sonoma: Varied by sub-region — volcanic in Sonoma Mountain, sandy loam in Russian River Valley. Paso Robles: Calcareous and siliceous shale. Central Valley: Deep, fertile alluvial soils — suited to high-volume production."}, "20": {"name": "Oregon, Washington & New York", "climate": "Oregon (Willamette Valley): Cool maritime. Rain shadow east of Coast Range but still wet winters. Long, mild growing seasons with dry summers. Similar latitude to Burgundy. Hazards: Autumn rain during harvest, frost. Washington (Columbia Valley): Continental desert — extreme temperature swings. Very dry (<200mm rain), irrigation essential. Rain shadow from Cascades. Long sunshine hours. Hot days, cold nights = high sugar + retained acidity. New York (Finger Lakes): Cool continental. Deep glacial lakes moderate temperatures, extending the growing season. Cold winters limit variety choice.", "winemaking": "Oregon: Burgundian philosophy dominates — small lots, whole-cluster fermentation, French oak, minimal intervention. Oregon Pinot Noir is typically lighter, more aromatic than California. Chardonnay increasingly made in Burgundian style. Washington: Modern winemaking with temperature control. Emphasis on ripe, concentrated fruit. Both French and American oak used. Cabernet Sauvignon and Merlot dominate. Syrah is emerging. Finger Lakes: Cool-fermented Riesling in stainless steel to preserve acidity and aromatics. Dry, semi-dry, and sweet styles produced.", "traps": ["Oregon = cool/maritime = Pinot Noir. Washington = warm/continental = Cabernet Sauvignon/Merlot. The Cascades divide them. Do not confuse.", "Oregon requires 90% of named variety on label (not the federal 75%).", "Washington's Columbia Valley is a desert — irrigation is essential. Rain shadow from Cascades. *"], "takeaways": ["Oregon = maritime, Pinot Noir (Willamette Valley), 90% varietal labelling rule", "Washington = continental, rain shadow, irrigation required, Cab Sauv/Merlot/Syrah", "Finger Lakes = cool continental, Riesling. Long Island = maritime, Bordeaux varieties"], "mc": [{"q": "Where do we find the Willamette Valley?", "o": ["California", "Washington State", "Western Australia", "Oregon"], "a": "d", "e": "The Willamette Valley is Oregon's premier wine region, best known for its elegant Pinot Noir."}], "soil": "Oregon (Willamette Valley): Volcanic (Jory — reddish basaltic clay) and marine sedimentary (Willakenzie — sandstone and siltstone). Jory is the most prized for Pinot Noir. Washington (Columbia Valley): Sandy, silty loess over basalt. Very well-drained. Ancient flood deposits (Missoula Floods). Low organic matter forces deep roots. Finger Lakes: Glacial soils — shale, limestone, gravel. Steep lakeside slopes with good drainage and air circulation.", "sq": [{"q": "How does Oregon's Pinot Noir differ from California's?", "a": "Oregon: cooler maritime climate (Willamette Valley). Lighter body, higher acidity, more aromatic — earth, red fruit, spice. Burgundian philosophy. 90% varietal labelling rule (stricter than US 75%). California Pinot Noir (Sonoma Coast, Carneros) tends to be riper, more fruit-forward, and richer."}, {"q": "Describe the climate and key varieties of Washington State.", "a": "Columbia Valley: continental desert in Cascade rain shadow. Very dry (<200mm rain), irrigation essential. Long sunshine hours (more than Napa), hot days, very cold nights. Key varieties: Cabernet Sauvignon, Merlot, Syrah (reds); Riesling, Chardonnay (whites). Walla Walla is the premium sub-region."}, {"q": "What are the key wine regions of New York State?", "a": "Finger Lakes: cool continental, deep glacial lakes moderate climate. Best US Riesling (dry, semi-dry, sweet). Also Cabernet Franc. Long Island: maritime, moderated by ocean. Bordeaux varieties (Cabernet Franc, Merlot). North Fork is the main sub-region."}, {"q": "Why is the Cascade mountain range significant for Washington viticulture?", "a": "The Cascades create a rain shadow to the east, making the Columbia Valley a desert with less than 200mm annual rainfall. This means irrigation is essential (from Columbia River). The dry conditions reduce disease pressure, while the continental climate provides intense sunshine and dramatic diurnal temperature swings."}]}, "21": {"name": "Canada", "climate": "Classification: Cool to cold continental. Extreme winters. Key Influences: Lakes moderate temperatures: Niagara = Lake Ontario; Okanagan = Okanagan Lake. Short but warm growing seasons.", "winemaking": "Icewine Okanagan Valley Merlot, Pinot Noir, Desert-like climate in (BC) Pinot Gris, Syrah, south (hot days, cold Riesling nights). Lake moderates. Quality still wines.", "traps": ["Icewine grapes must freeze NATURALLY on the vine. Artificial freezing is not permitted.", "Vidal is the most commonly used grape for Icewine, not Riesling. Vidal is a hybrid — thicker skin, better cold resistance. *"], "takeaways": ["Icewine = naturally frozen grapes at -8C, pressed frozen. Vidal (most common) or Riesling (premium)", "Niagara Peninsula: Ontario, Lake Ontario moderation, Icewine capital", "Okanagan Valley: BC, desert climate, quality still wines"], "soil": "Niagara Peninsula: Clay, loam, and gravel. Lake Ontario moderates temperatures and extends the frost-free season. The Niagara Escarpment provides varied aspects and elevations. Okanagan Valley: Sandy, glacial soils with gravel and silt. Desert-like conditions in the south. Lakeside vineyards benefit from reflected heat and moderating influence of Okanagan Lake.", "mc": [{"q": "What is the most commonly used grape for Canadian Icewine?", "o": ["Riesling", "Chardonnay", "Vidal", "Cabernet Franc"], "a": "c", "e": "Vidal is the most commonly used grape for Icewine, not Riesling. Vidal is a French hybrid with thicker skin and better cold resistance, making it more reliable for Icewine production. Riesling Icewine is considered premium but riskier to produce."}, {"q": "At what minimum temperature must grapes be harvested for Canadian Icewine?", "o": ["-5°C", "-7°C", "-8°C", "-10°C"], "a": "c", "e": "Canadian Icewine grapes must be naturally frozen on the vine and harvested at -8°C or below. Artificial freezing is not permitted. The grapes are pressed while still frozen, concentrating sugars and acids."}, {"q": "Which Canadian wine region is known as the 'Icewine capital'?", "o": ["Okanagan Valley", "Prince Edward County", "Niagara Peninsula", "Annapolis Valley"], "a": "c", "e": "The Niagara Peninsula in Ontario, moderated by Lake Ontario, is the world's leading Icewine-producing region. Its reliable cold winters and lake-moderated growing season make it ideal for both Icewine and still wine production."}], "sq": [{"q": "Describe the Icewine production process.", "a": "Grapes left on vine into winter. Harvested at -8°C or below (naturally frozen, no artificial freezing). Pressed while still frozen — water stays as ice, concentrating sugars and acids in the small amount of extracted juice. Fermented slowly. Result: intensely sweet, high-acidity wine with pure fruit character."}, {"q": "Compare Niagara Peninsula and Okanagan Valley.", "a": "Niagara (Ontario): cool continental, moderated by Lake Ontario. Best known for Icewine (Vidal, Riesling). Also Chardonnay, Pinot Noir, Cabernet Franc still wines. Okanagan (BC): desert-like climate in south (hot days, cold nights), lake-moderated. Quality still wines: Merlot, Pinot Noir, Pinot Gris, Syrah, Riesling."}, {"q": "Why is Vidal preferred over Riesling for Icewine?", "a": "Vidal is a French hybrid with thicker skin, providing better cold resistance and protection against winter damage. It is more reliable in extreme cold. Riesling Icewine is considered premium (more elegant, higher acidity) but is riskier — thin skins are more prone to damage and loss."}]}, "22": {"name": "Chile", "climate": "Classification: Mediterranean (central) with significant variation by proximity to coast, Andes, or desert. Key Influences: Cold Humboldt Current cools coastal regions dramatically. Andes provide altitude for cooling and snowmelt for irrigation. Rain shadow between Coastal Range and Andes creates dry conditions. South is wetter and cooler. Hazards: Drought (north), phylloxera is absent (so own-rooted vines).", "winemaking": "Winemaking Modern, clean winemaking with stainless steel and oak. International styles for export. Increasingly, producers are exploring cooler-climate sites (coast and altitude) and old-vine heritage grapes (Pais, Carignan).", "traps": ["Carmenere was confused with Merlot until 1994. It is Chile's signature grape, not Merlot.", "Chile is phylloxera-free, so vines are ungrafted (own-rooted).", "The Humboldt Current is a COLD current — it cools the coast. Don't confuse with the Gulf Stream (warm). *"], "takeaways": ["Carmenere = Chile's signature grape, confused with Merlot until 1994", "Phylloxera-free = ungrafted vines", "Humboldt Current (cold) cools coast: Casablanca, Leyda = cool-climate", "Maipo = top Cabernet Sauvignon; Colchagua = warm, full-bodied reds"], "mc": [{"q": "Carmenère is an important grape variety grown in:", "o": ["Chile", "Argentina", "Australia", "South Africa"], "a": "a", "e": "Carmenère was long mistaken for Merlot in Chile and is now considered the country's signature red grape variety."}, {"q": "In climatic terms, which weather pattern can cause drought to\noccur in Chile?", "o": ["La Niña", "El Niño", "Parral", "Humboldt"], "a": "a", "e": "El Niño brings increased rainfall to Chile, while La Niña is associated with severe drought conditions."}, {"q": "The Humboldt Current affects which wine-producing country?", "o": ["Argentina", "South Australia", "Chile", "South Africa"], "a": "c", "e": "The Humboldt Current is a cold ocean current flowing northwards along the Pacific coast of South America. It cools coastal wine regions such as Casablanca and Leyda."}], "sq": [{"q": "Where does Carmenère originate and which Chilean sub-regions produce premium examples?", "a": "Originally from Bordeaux. Premium Chilean sub-regions: Aconcagua, Colchagua, Cachapoal, Limarí."}, {"q": "Why does Carmenère need warm or hot, sunny areas?", "a": "It is a late-ripening variety that becomes distinctly herbaceous when underripe (tomato stalk, mint, green pepper). Warm conditions are needed for full ripeness and to avoid overtly green notes."}, {"q": "How are high tannin levels achieved in premium Carmenère?", "a": "Increased extraction through higher temperature ferments, pumping over, punching down, rack-and-return, rotary fermenters. New oak can also add tannic structure."}, {"q": "How are roasted coffee and chocolate notes achieved in premium Carmenère?", "a": "By using heavily toasted barrels during fermentation and maturation to impart these secondary aromas."}, {"q": "Name two cool-climate sub-regions in Chile.", "a": "Casablanca, San Antonio, Leyda (any two)."}, {"q": "Describe three climatic influences that cool Chile's coastal wine zones.", "a": "1) Humboldt Current flows from Antarctica along the coast. 2) Prevailing winds blow cool air inland along river valleys. 3) Cool and warm air meeting creates fogs. Also: cooling from Andes and coastal mountain ranges."}, {"q": "Name three winemaking techniques for premium Chilean Chardonnay.", "a": "1) Controlled oxidation via whole-bunch pressing (improves ageability). 2) MLF for rounder, creamier mouthfeel. 3) Yeast autolysis/fine lees ageing with bâtonnage for richness. Also acceptable: (new) oak fermentation/maturation."}, {"q": "Where in Chile would you find Chardonnay with structure, elegance and restraint?", "a": "Limarí or Elquí Valley."}], "soil": "Maipo Valley: Alluvial soils with gravel and stones from the Andes. Well-drained, ideal for Cabernet Sauvignon. Alto Maipo (foothills) has rockier, poorer soils producing more structured wines. Casablanca/Leyda (coastal): Clay and granite with limited water retention — coastal fog provides moisture. Colchagua: Alluvial and colluvial soils, deeper and more fertile than Maipo. Chile is phylloxera-free, so vines are ungrafted on their own roots."}, "23": {"name": "Argentina", "climate": "Classification: Continental, semi-arid desert. Very dry; irrigation essential (Andes snowmelt). Key Influences: High altitude is the defining feature (Mendoza vineyards 600--1500m+; Salta/Cafayate up to 3000m). Altitude provides UV intensity, large diurnal temperature range, and cooler nights. Andes rain shadow = very little rain. Hazards: Hail (major threat — hail nets common), zonda wind (hot, dry), drought.", "winemaking": "Winemaking Malbec: Extended maceration for deep colour and tannin extraction. Oak ageing in French barriques is standard for premium wines. Cap management techniques (punch-down, pump-over, rack-and-return) are used for concentration. High-altitude fruit naturally produces thick-skinned grapes with intense colour. Torrontes: Reductive winemaking in stainless steel at cool temperatures to preserve delicate floral aromatics. No oak. Usually released young. No malolactic fermentation.", "traps": ["Malbec is originally from Cahors, France (where it's called Cot). Argentina adopted it and made it world-famous.", "Altitude is Argentina's key viticultural advantage, not latitude. Mendoza is warm at ground level; altitude provides cooling.", "Torrontes is NOT related to Torrontes of Spain. It is a cross of Muscat of Alexandria and Criolla Chica. *"], "takeaways": ["Malbec = Argentina's signature red (from Cahors). Mendoza is the heartland", "Altitude is the key: higher = cooler, more elegant, more structured", "Uco Valley = premium high-altitude sub-region of Mendoza", "Torrontes = signature white, aromatic, best from Salta at extreme altitude", "Semi-arid desert; irrigation from Andes snowmelt is essential"], "mc": [{"q": "Viticulture in Cafayate is significantly influenced by:", "o": ["On-shore fog", "Noble rot", "High rainfall", "High altitude"], "a": "d", "e": "Cafayate is located in the Salta province of Argentina, boasting some of the highest vineyards in the world."}, {"q": "The rainfall levels in Mendoza:", "o": ["Present no particular problem", "Are so high that rot is a persistent threat", "Mean irrigation is only needed in very dry years", "Mean irrigation is essential"], "a": "d", "e": "Mendoza sits in the rain shadow of the Andes, making it practically a desert that relies entirely on irrigation from Andean snowmelt."}, {"q": "Which of the following winemaking techniques is typically used for\nTorrontés?", "o": ["Malolactic fermentation", "Warm fermentation in barrels", "Cool fermentation in inert vessels", "Maturation in new oak barrels"], "a": "c", "e": "Torrontés is a highly aromatic grape variety. Cool fermentation in stainless steel protects its delicate floral and fruity aromatics."}], "sq": [{"q": "Describe the Uco Valley.", "a": "Highest vineyards in Mendoza (900-1500m). Best quality fruit. Cool nights → higher acidity, fresher, more floral wines."}, {"q": "Why is pergola training used for Torrontés?", "a": "High canopy avoids ground heat. Dense shade protects from intense UV at high altitude."}, {"q": "Describe the aromas of Argentine Torrontés.", "a": "Stone fruits (apricot, peach), tropical fruits (melon, passionfruit), intensely perfumed and floral (blossom, jasmine, chamomile)."}, {"q": "Where in Mendoza would you source premium Torrontés and why?", "a": "Uco Valley. Vineyards at 900-1500m (highest in Mendoza) ensure cooler growing conditions with very cold nights, producing extremely fresh wines with high natural acidity and enhanced aromatics."}, {"q": "Name another district outside Mendoza for premium Torrontés.", "a": "Salta Province — Cafayate."}, {"q": "What is a major hazard in Mendoza and how can growers combat it?", "a": "Hail. Combat: 1) Strategic planting across broader areas so only localised damage occurs. 2) Netting the vines (expensive but effective)."}, {"q": "Describe three cap management techniques for deep, concentrated Malbec.", "a": "1) Punching down — paddles push floating cap into juice, extracting colour/tannin/flavour. 2) Pumping over — juice drawn from bottom and sprayed over cap. 3) Rack and return — wine drained from vessel then reintroduced over cap for intense extraction."}, {"q": "Where in France is Malbec found and how does the style differ from Argentina?", "a": "Cahors AOC. Cahors Malbec has a longer growing season → more tannic/structured. Cooler climate (warm continental vs hot continental) → brighter acidities."}], "soil": "Mendoza: Alluvial soils — sand, clay, and gravel deposited by Andean rivers. Well-drained. Higher-altitude sites in Uco Valley (900-1500m) have rockier, calcareous soils with limestone — producing more mineral, structured Malbec. Salta (Cafayate): Sandy, calcareous soils at extreme altitude (up to 3000m). Very poor fertility, forcing deep roots and low yields."}, "24": {"name": "South Africa", "climate": "Classification: Mediterranean (warm, dry summers). Moderated by Atlantic and Indian Ocean influences. Key Influences: Cold Benguela Current from the Antarctic cools the western coast (similar to Humboldt Current in Chile). Southeast Trade Winds (Cape Doctor) reduce disease. Altitude and proximity to the ocean provide additional cooling. Hazards: Drought, wind damage, bushveld fires.", "winemaking": "Winemaking Chenin Blanc: Three distinct styles — (1) inexpensive, high-volume in stainless steel for fresh, simple wines; (2) premium oaked with barrel fermentation, lees contact, and batonnage for rich, complex whites; (3) old bush vine Chenin from Swartland/Paarl with natural fermentation and minimal intervention. Pinotage: Varies from fruity, carbonic-maceration style to serious, oak-aged with extended maceration. Cabernet Sauvignon/Bordeaux blends: French oak ageing, traditional Bordeaux-style winemaking in Stellenbosch.", "traps": ["Pinotage = Pinot Noir x Cinsault (NOT Cinsaut x Pinot Noir in terms of the cross — but both are correct). It is unique to South Africa.", "Chenin Blanc is called Steen locally. South Africa has more old-vine Chenin Blanc than any other country.", "The Benguela Current is COLD (not warm). It is what allows cool-climate viticulture near the coast. *"], "takeaways": ["Chenin Blanc (Steen) = most-planted grape; old vines in Swartland/Paarl are world-class", "Pinotage = Pinot Noir x Cinsault, unique to South Africa", "Benguela Current (cold) cools the coast, similar to Chile's Humboldt", "Stellenbosch = prestige reds; Walker Bay/Elgin = cool-climate Pinot/Chardonnay", "WO system: regions > districts > wards. 85% from named area"], "sq": [{"q": "What is the most cultivated white grape in South Africa?", "a": "Chenin Blanc."}, {"q": "Describe three styles of SA Chenin Blanc.", "a": "1) Inexpensive blends: high-volume, irrigated, Breede River Valley, stainless steel. 2) Premium hot-climate: Paarl, late harvest, heavy oak, rich/powerful, up to 15%. 3) Premium cool-climate: Walker Bay/Stellenbosch/Elgin, fresh, high acidity, ~13%, light lees, elegant."}, {"q": "Name three climatic influences of the Western Cape.", "a": "1) Benguela Current from Southern Ocean brings cool air. 2) Cape Doctor south-easterly wind cools inland areas. 3) Mountain ranges provide cooler high-altitude sites and shadowed areas."}, {"q": "What are the parent varieties of Pinotage?", "a": "Cinsault × Pinot Noir."}, {"q": "Where would you source grapes for an inexpensive SA red blend vs a premium white?", "a": "Inexpensive red: Breede River Valley (Worcester, Robertson) — hot, dry, fertile, irrigated, high yields. Premium white: Stellenbosch, Walker Bay, or Elgin — cooler, Benguela current, varied soils/altitudes, old bush vines."}], "mc": [{"q": "Where is the wine producing district of Constantia?", "o": ["Chile", "Australia", "New Zealand", "South Africa"], "a": "d", "e": "Constantia is a historic and highly regarded ward on the Cape Peninsula near Cape Town, South Africa."}], "soil": "Stellenbosch: Granite decomposed into sandy, well-drained soils. Higher slopes have weathered sandstone (Table Mountain series). Swartland: Shale and granite — bush vines on dryland (unirrigated). Contributes to low yields and concentrated fruit. Walker Bay/Hemel-en-Aarde: Shale-derived clay soils, cool maritime influence. Suited to Pinot Noir and Chardonnay. Constantia: Ancient granite soils on the slopes of Table Mountain, cooled by both Atlantic and False Bay breezes."}, "25": {"name": "Australia", "climate": "Overview: Ranges from very hot (Barossa, McLaren Vale, Hunter Valley) to cool (Tasmania, Yarra Valley, Adelaide Hills). Maritime and continental influences both present. Key Influences: Southern Ocean and Antarctic currents cool southern regions. Altitude provides cooling (Eden Valley, Adelaide Hills). Hunter Valley: moderated by cloud cover and sea breezes despite warm temperatures.", "winemaking": "Winemaking Shiraz: Australia's most important grape. Styles range from blockbuster (Barossa) to elegant (Yarra Valley, cooler sites). Oak ageing in American and/or French oak. Hunter Valley Semillon: Unique Australian style. Harvested early (10--11% ABV), unoaked, bottled young. Develops remarkable complexity with age (honey, toast, lanolin). This is a key exam topic. Screwcaps: Australia (and NZ) pioneered the use of screwcap closures for premium wines, especially Riesling (Clare Valley). Important industry innovation.", "traps": ["Hunter Valley Semillon is picked EARLY, low alcohol, unoaked. It is NOT a rich, oaky style. The ageing potential comes from acidity, not oak.", "Coonawarra is famous for terra rossa soil (red soil over limestone) and Cabernet Sauvignon. Not Shiraz.", "Australia calls Syrah 'Shiraz.' Same grape, different name. Do not treat them as different grapes.", "Eden Valley is cooler than Barossa Valley due to altitude, despite being adjacent. Riesling in Eden Valley, Shiraz in Barossa. *"], "takeaways": ["Barossa = iconic Australian Shiraz (warm, rich, old vines). Eden Valley = Riesling (cooler, altitude)", "Hunter Valley Semillon: early-picked, low alcohol, unoaked, ages brilliantly --- unique style", "Coonawarra = terra rossa soil + Cabernet Sauvignon", "Margaret River = Bordeaux-like climate, premium Cab Sauv and Chardonnay", "GI system: zones > regions > sub-regions. 85% rule. Geography only", "Clare Valley pioneered screwcap closures for premium Riesling"], "mc": [{"q": "Rutherglen is renowned for which style of wine?", "o": ["Sparkling", "Fortified", "Light white wines", "Light red wines"], "a": "b", "e": "Rutherglen in Victoria, Australia, is world-famous for its sweet, luscious fortified Muscat wines."}, {"q": "What is the Margaret River's climate?", "o": ["Cool maritime", "Moderate maritime", "Warm maritime", "Warm Mediterranean"], "a": "d", "e": "Margaret River in Western Australia has a warm Mediterranean climate with reliable sunshine, tempered by the Indian Ocean."}, {"q": "Which Australian wine area is NOT well known for producing Pinot\nNoir?", "o": ["Mornington Peninsula", "Clare Valley", "Yarra Valley", "Tasmania"], "a": "b", "e": "Clare Valley is a warmer region known primarily for Riesling and Shiraz. Mornington Peninsula, Yarra Valley, and Tasmania are all renowned cool-climate Pinot Noir regions."}], "sq": [{"q": "How do natural factors affect Shiraz style in hot Australian regions?", "a": "Warmer climates ripen thick-skinned Shiraz fully → full-bodied, black fruit, intense, earthy/spicy, higher alcohol. Can display leather aromas with age."}, {"q": "What can a winemaker do to create a more refined Australian Shiraz?", "a": "Harvest earlier (lower alcohol, less jammy). Gentler cap management (less extraction). Whole bunch inclusion (fresher character). Post-fermentation maceration (smoother tannins). Larger/older oak barrels."}, {"q": "What grape is commonly blended with Australian Shiraz?", "a": "Cabernet Sauvignon."}, {"q": "What is the distinctive soil type in Coonawarra?", "a": "Terra Rossa — clay/loam/limestone high in iron."}, {"q": "What characteristics distinguish Coonawarra Cabernet Sauvignon?", "a": "Intense herbaceous notes with distinctive menthol and eucalypt aromas."}, {"q": "Name two bulk-production regions in South-Eastern Australia.", "a": "Riverina, Riverland, Murray-Darling (any two)."}], "soil": "Barossa Valley: Sandy loam over clay subsoil. Deep, old soils (some vines 150+ years old on own roots — phylloxera-free). McLaren Vale: Varied — sand, clay, and limestone. Maritime influence from Gulf St Vincent. Eden Valley: Sandy loam and quartz at higher altitude than Barossa. Cooler. Coonawarra: Terra rossa — distinctive red loam over limestone. Key exam term. Excellent drainage and heat retention. Ideal for Cabernet Sauvignon. Hunter Valley: Heavy clay and volcanic basalt. Challenging — poor drainage but produces distinctive wines. Margaret River: Gravelly loam over granite. Bordeaux-like drainage."}, "26": {"name": "New Zealand", "climate": "Classification: Maritime. Cool to moderate. Long, sunny growing seasons with moderate temperatures. Key Influences: Surrounded by ocean — no point is far from the sea. Latitude varies: Marlborough (\\~41°S) is cooler than Hawke's Bay (\\~39°S). Mountain ranges create rain shadows (e.g., Canterbury/Waipara). Central Otago is the most continental. Hazards: Autumn rain, frost, high UV intensity.", "winemaking": "Winemaking Sauvignon Blanc: Stainless steel fermentation to preserve aromatics. Typically unoaked. Cool-fermented. The Marlborough style (pungent gooseberry, passionfruit, herbaceous) has become a global benchmark. Pinot Noir: French oak ageing (light to moderate). Central Otago produces more concentrated, structured styles than Martinborough or Marlborough. Screwcaps: New Zealand, along with Australia, widely adopted screwcaps for even premium wines.", "traps": ["Central Otago is the only continental climate region in New Zealand. All others are maritime.", "Marlborough is on the South Island, not the North. Hawke's Bay is on the North Island.", "New Zealand's most-planted grape is now Sauvignon Blanc, not Muller-Thurgau (which dominated historically). *"], "takeaways": ["Marlborough = NZ's largest region, defines global Sauvignon Blanc style (pungent, herbaceous)", "Central Otago = most southerly significant wine region, continental, concentrated Pinot Noir", "Hawke's Bay = warmest, Bordeaux varieties. Gimblett Gravels = premium sub-region", "Almost entirely maritime climate except Central Otago (continental)"], "sq": [{"q": "Name and describe two distinct areas of Marlborough for Sauvignon Blanc.", "a": "Awatere Valley: colder, drier, windier → lighter wines, brighter acidity, more mineral. Wairau Valley: warmer, rainier → more pronounced aromatics, typical Marlborough style."}, {"q": "Why is Marlborough SB so vibrant yet acidic?", "a": "2,200+ sunshine hours (more than most regions) + extensive canopy management = pronounced aromas. Cool windy conditions preserve bright acidity."}, {"q": "How can winemakers make rounder Sauvignon Blanc?", "a": "1) Blend with Sémillon. 2) Light oak maturation. 3) Yeast autolysis, MLF, and/or wild fermentations."}], "soil": "Marlborough: Stony, free-draining alluvial gravels in the Wairau Valley. Southern Valleys have more clay. The stony soils reflect heat and stress vines, concentrating flavours. Hawke's Bay (Gimblett Gravels): Old riverbed with free-draining gravels — warm, well-drained, ideal for Bordeaux varieties. The gravels absorb and radiate heat. Central Otago: Schist and loess over ancient mica schist bedrock. Glacial soils, very free-draining. Martinborough: River terraces with free-draining gravels — similar to Burgundy conditions.", "mc": [{"q": "Which New Zealand region has a continental rather than maritime climate?", "o": ["Marlborough", "Hawke's Bay", "Martinborough", "Central Otago"], "a": "d", "e": "Central Otago is the only continental climate region in New Zealand and the world's most southerly significant wine region. All other NZ regions are maritime. Its extreme temperature swings produce concentrated, structured Pinot Noir."}, {"q": "What is the most-planted grape variety in New Zealand?", "o": ["Pinot Noir", "Chardonnay", "Müller-Thurgau", "Sauvignon Blanc"], "a": "d", "e": "Sauvignon Blanc is now New Zealand's most-planted grape by a large margin. Marlborough Sauvignon Blanc has become a global benchmark for the variety. Müller-Thurgau historically dominated but has been largely replaced."}, {"q": "What is the premium sub-region within Hawke's Bay?", "o": ["Wairau Valley", "Gimblett Gravels", "Waipara", "Awatere Valley"], "a": "b", "e": "Gimblett Gravels is an acclaimed sub-region of Hawke's Bay, defined by its free-draining, heat-retentive old riverbed gravels. It produces outstanding Bordeaux-variety reds, particularly Cabernet Sauvignon and Merlot blends."}]}};
